(1941). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"John Gould's Australian Prospectus\", ''Emu'', 42 (1942), 74\u201384. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Birds of the Gilbert Diary\", ''Emu'', 44 (1944), 131\u2013150. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"An Explorer and His Birds. John Gilbert\"s Discoveries in 1844\u20135\" (1945). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"The Diaries of S. W. Jackson\", ''Emu'', 58 (1958), 75\u201376. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"J. R. Elsey, Surgeon, Naturalist, Explorer\", ''Queensland Naturalist'', 17 (3/4) (1964), 60\u201370. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Some Early Letters in Australian Ornithology\", ''Emu'', 63 (1964). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"J. R. Elsey, Explorer of the Never-Never\", ''Journal of the Royal Australian Historical Society'', 52 (1966). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Dudley Dickison - Student of Birds and Books\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 84 (8) (1967), 251\u2013253. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Obituary. Gilbert Roscoe Gannon\", ''Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales'', 89 (1968), 12. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Obituaries: Roy Percy Cooper\", ''Emu'', 77 (2) (1977), 88. \n==Journal articles about Alexander Chisholm==\n* McGill, A. R., \"Alexander Hugh Chisholm\", ''Emu'', 77 (1977), 232\u2013235. \n* Willis, J. H., \"Alexander Hugh Chisholm, OBE, CMZS., C.F.A.O.U. (1890\u20131977). An Appreciation\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 94 (5) (1977), 188\u2013190.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Alec H. Chisholm in the [http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P001137b.htm ''Encyclopaedia of Australian Science'']\n*Biography in [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chisholm-alexander-hugh-alec-9741 ''The Australian Dictionary of Biography'']\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chisholm, Alexander Hugh}}\n[[Category:Australian ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Australian nature writers]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Australian naturalists]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian editors]]\n[[Category:Australian encyclopedists]]\n[[Category:Australian broadcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}\n'''Alexander Hugh Chisholm''' [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] [[Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales|FRZS]] (28 March 1890 \u2014 10 July 1977) also known as '''Alec Chisholm''', was a noted Australian naturalist, [[journalist]], [[editing|newspaper editor]], [[author]] and [[ornithologist]].  He was a member of the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] (RAOU), President of the RAOU 1939\u20131940, and editor of its journal the ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]'' from 1926 to 1928.  In 1941 he was elected a [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union Fellows|Fellow of the RAOU]] in 1941 and the previous year he had been the first recipient of the [[Australian Natural History Medallion]] for his work in ornithology and popularising natural history. Chisholm was a prolific and popular writer of articles and books, mainly on birds and nature but also on history, literature and biography.<ref>{{Cite book|title=IDLING IN GREEN PLACES : a life of alec chisholm.|last=MCGREGOR, RUSSELL.|date=2019|publisher=AUSTRALIAN SCHOLARLY PUB|isbn=978-1925801996|oclc=1119561712}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.environmentandsociety.org/arcadia/mateship-birds-australian-plea-conservation-0|title=Mateship with Birds: An Australian Plea for Conservation {{!}} Environment & Society Portal|website=www.environmentandsociety.org|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> He is not to be confused with his near-contemporary the anti-semite and enthusiast of Germany's [[Nazism|National Socialists]], the Melbourne University linguist Alan R. Chisholm.<ref>{{Citation | author1=Bird, David S. (David Samuel.) | title=Nazi dreamtime : Australian enthusiasts for Hitler's Germany | publication-date=2012 | publisher=Australian Scholarly | isbn=978-1-921875-42-7 }}</ref> \n\n== Early Life ==\nAlec H. Chisholm was born on 28 March 1890 at [[Maryborough, Victoria|Maryborough]], Victoria, seventh of eight children. His father was Colin Chisholm, an Australian-born grocer, and his wife Charlotte, n\u00e9e Kennedy, from Scotland.<ref>Tess Kloot, 'Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890\u20131977)', Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 13, (MUP), 1993</ref> He was educated at Maryborough State School until the age of 12. \n\n== Conservationist ==\nBy the time he began work as a journalist, Chisholm already had a name as a conservationist. In 1907, aged seventeen, he joined the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]] and during the next year wrote six articles in the organisation's journal, the ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]''. In the ''Maryborough and Dunolly Advertiser'' he campaigned in 1908 against the killing of [[Egret|egrets]] for feathers for women's hats, a crusade in which he won support from Australian poet [[Mary Gilmore|Dame Mary Gilmore]]. In 1911 he was employed at the newspaper as a journalist, leaving in 1915 for a position at the ''Brisbane Mail''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P001137b.htm|title=Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890 - 1977)|website=Encyclopedia of Australian Science|publisher=University of Melbourne eScholarship Research Centre|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Kloot|first=Tess|title=Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (Alec) (1890\u20131977)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chisholm-alexander-hugh-alec-9741|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> He continued to campaign for the conservation of Australia's birds, animals and plants for the rest of his life.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The flight of the emu : a hundred years of Australian ornithology, 1901-2001|last=Robin, Libby, 1956-|date=2001|publisher=Melbourne University Press|isbn=0522849873|oclc=49001691}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\n\nOn 8 November 1923 Chisholm married Olive May Haseler in Brisbane.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article20675427|title=PRE-WEDDING DINNER.|date=7 November 1923|newspaper=[[The Brisbane Courier]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|issue=20,528|location=Queensland, Australia|page=18|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> They had one daughter,  Deirdre, who was born on 26 December 1924. From 1964, Olive Chisholm's health deteriorated seriously. Alec cared for her as best he could until late 1968, when she was committed to Balmoral Hill Convalescent Home, where she died in 1970. By this time, his own health was in serious decline, although he continued living alone in a small flat in Sydney's Cremorne Point until his death in 1977.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McGill|first=A. R.|date=1977-10-01|title=Alexander Hugh Chisholm|journal=Emu - Austral Ornithology|volume=77|issue=4|pages=232\u2013235|doi=10.1071/MU9770232|issn=0158-4197}}</ref>\n\n== Journalist and Editor ==\nChisholm worked \u00a0as a journalist in Queensland from 1915 to 1922, then moved to Sydney \u00a0where he became news editor of the ''Daily Telegraph'' and later editor of the ''Sunday Pictorial''. After moving to Melbourne in 1933, he was for many years editor of the ''Australasian'', before being appointed editor of [[The Argus (Melbourne)|''The Argus'']] in June 1937.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74199326|title=Editor Of Melbourne \"Argus\" Retires|date=30 June 1937|newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|location=South Australia|page=22|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article25409635|title=\"ARGUS\" CHANGES|date=30 June 1937|newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart)|The Mercury]]|accessdate=6 March 2018|issue=20,780|location=Tasmania, Australia|volume=CXLVI|page=9|via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>  He spent ten years, from 1948 to 1958, editing the ten-volume ''[[Australian Encyclopaedia]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10070570 |title=Chisholm, Alec H. (Alec Hugh), 1890-1977 |website=Trove |publisher=National Library of Australia |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> for which he was awarded the [[Order of the British Empire]]. Chisholm was also editor of ''[[The Victorian Naturalist]]'' and ''[[Who's Who in Australia]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/11328795|title=Who's who in Australia: (incorporating Johns's notable Australians / compiled and edited by Alec H. Chisholm|website=Trove|publisher=National Library of Australia|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> In his late years he wrote several entries on ornithologists, naturalists and explorers in the [[Australian Dictionary of Biography|''Australian Dictionary of Biography'']]. He was a contributor of articles to a number of publications, including ''[[Walkabout (magazine)|Walkabout]]'', the latter mostly on Australian bird life and history.\n\n== Historian ==\nVisiting England in 1938, Chisholm discovered a large number of documents relating to the nineteenth-century ornithologist [[John Gould]]. They included the diary kept by Gould's principal collector, [[John Gilbert (naturalist)|John Gilbert]], during his participation in [[Ludwig Leichhardt]]\u2019s 1844-45 expedition to Port Essington. This diary became the foundation of Chisholm's 1941 book, ''Strange New World''. He published several later works of history, but none achieved the popularity or notoriety of his Gilbert and Leichhardt book.<ref>{{Cite book|title=IDLING IN GREEN PLACES : a life of alec chisholm.|last=MCGREGOR, RUSSELL.|date=2019|publisher=AUSTRALIAN SCHOLARLY PUB|isbn=978-1925801996|oclc=1119561712}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and offices==\n* 1918\u20131922 \u2013 adviser and lecturer on natural history for the Queensland Government\n* 1919\u20131922 \u2013 president, Queensland Gould League of Bird Lovers\n* 1920\u20131922 \u2013 president, Queensland Naturalists' Club\n* 1920\u20131922 \u2013 editor, ''Queensland Naturalist''\n* 1922 \u2013 corresponding fellow, [[American Ornithologists' Union]]\n* 1926\u20131928 \u2013 editor, ''[[Emu (journal)|Emu]]''\n* 1934 \u2013 president, [[Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales]]\n* 1937\u20131938 \u2013 president, Victorian Bird Observers' Club\n* 1937\u20131938 \u2013 president, [[Field Naturalists Club of Victoria]]\n* 1939\u20131940 \u2013 president, [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]]\n* 1939\u20131948 \u2013 editor, ''[[The Victorian Naturalist]]''\n* 1940 \u2013 Australian Natural History Medallion (Field Naturalists Club of Victoria)\n* 1940 \u2013 inaugural recipient of the [[Australian Natural History Medallion]]\n* [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]]\n* Fellow of the Royal Zoological Society\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Australian Historical Society]]\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Historical Society of Queensland]]\n* Member of the [[British Ornithologists' Union]]\n\n==Books==\n\n* Chisholm, A. H., ''The Story of Elizabeth Gould'' (Melbourne: Hawthorn Press, 1944).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Strange New World: The Adventures of John Gilbert and Ludwig Leichardt'' (Sydney: Angus & Robertson, 1955). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Ferdinand von Mueller'' (Melbourne: Oxford University Press, 1962).\n*\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Mateship with Birds''. [[Whitcombe & Tombs Ltd]]: Melbourne.(1922)\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Birds and Green Places. A book of Australian nature gossip''. J.M. Dent & Sons Ltd: London.(1929)\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Nature Fantasy in Australia''. J.M. Dent & Sons Ltd: London.(1932).\n*\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Bird Wonders of Australia''. Angus & Robertson: Sydney. This book went though six editions, the last being issued in 1969.(1934).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''An Explorer and His Birds. [[John Gilbert (naturalist)|John Gilbert]]'s discoveries in 1844-45''. Brown, Prior, Anderson: Mebourne.(1945).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Making of a Sentimental Bloke : A sketch of the remarkable career of C.J. Dennis'', Georgian house: Melbourne.(1946).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Fairy Wrens''. F.W. Cheshire Pty Ltd: Melbourne.(1948).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''News from Nature. A selection of seasonal gossip''. Georgian House: Melbourne.(1948).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''Scots Wha Hae : History of the Royal Caledonian Society of Melbourne'', Angus & Robertson: Sydney. (1950).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Romance of the Lyrebird''. Angus & Robertson Pty Ltd: Sydney.(1960).\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, ''The Joy of the Earth''. Collins: Sydney.(1969). \n \n==Book sections==\n* Chisholm, A. H., [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010407b.htm \"Gilbert, John (1810?\u20131845)\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 441\u2013442. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010084b.htm \"Bennett, George (1804\u20131893), medical practitioner and naturalist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 85\u201386. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Gilbert, John (1810?\u20131845), naturalist and explorer\" in ''Journal of the Royal Australian Historical Society'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 441\u2013442. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010426b.htm \"Gould, Elizabeth (1804\u20131841), natural history artist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), p. 465. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A010427b.htm \"Gould, John (1804\u20131881), zoologist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 1 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1966), pp. 465\u2013467. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030453b.htm \"Coxen, Charles (1809\u20131876), naturalist and politician\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), pp. 487\u2013488. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030308b.htm \"Calvert, James Snowden (1825\u20131884), explorer and botanist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), p. 333. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030223b.htm \"Broinowski, Gracius Joseph (1837\u20131913), artist and ornithologist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), p. 239. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A030060b.htm \"Atkinson, Caroline Louisa Waring (1834\u20131872), naturalist and writer\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 3 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1969), pp. 59\u201360. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A040423b.htm \"Helms, Richard (1842\u20131914), zoologist and botanist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 4 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1972), p. 374. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A040141b.htm \"Elsey, Joseph Ravenscroft (1834\u20131857), surgeon, explorer and naturalist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Douglas Pike, ed., vol. 4 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1972), p. 139. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060004b.htm \"Ramsay, Edward Pierson (1842\u20131916), ornithologist and zoologist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn, ed., vol. 6 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1976), pp. 3\u20134. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A060411b.htm \"Wheelwright, Horace (Horatio) William (1815\u20131865)\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn, ed., vol. 6 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1976), pp. 383\u2013384. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A070191b.htm \"Barrett, Charles Leslie (1879\u20131959), naturalist and journalist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn and Geoffrey Serle, eds, vol. 7 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1979), p. 185. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A070605b.htm \"Cayley, Neville William (1886\u20131950), ornithologist and artist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', Bede Nairn and Geoffrey Serle, eds, vol. 7 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1979), pp. 596\u2013597. \n* Kloot, Tess, [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A130463b.htm \"Chisholm, Alexander Hugh (1890\u20131977), Journalist, Ornithologist and Encyclopaedist\"] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography'', John Ritchie, ed., vol. 13 (Melbourne: Melbourne University Press, 1993), pp. 422\u2013423. \n\n==Edited books==\n* Chisholm, A. H. ed., ''Journal of a Voyage to New South Wales with Sixty-five Plates of New Descript Animals, Birds, Lizards, Serpents, Curious Cones of Trees and other Natural Productions'' by John White, Esq. (Sydney: Angus & Robertson for Royal Australian Historical Society, 1962). \n\n==Journal articles==\n* Balmford, Peter, \"Newspapers as a Source of Information about Natural History\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 102 (1) (1985), 20\u201327. \n* Chisholm, A. H., \"The Ornithological History of Queensland\", ''Queensland Naturalist'', lii (1922), 66\u201379; 93\u2013101; 115\u2013123. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Some Letters from George Grey to John Gould\", ''Emu'', 38 (1938). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"John Gilbert. Some Letters to Gould\", ''Emu'', 38 (1938). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"The Story of John Gilbert.\", ''Emu'', 39 (1940), 156\u2013176. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Mrs John Gould and her Relations\", ''Emu'' (1941). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"John Gould's Australian Prospectus\", ''Emu'', 42 (1942), 74\u201384. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Birds of the Gilbert Diary\", ''Emu'', 44 (1944), 131\u2013150. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"An Explorer and His Birds. John Gilbert\"s Discoveries in 1844\u20135\" (1945). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"The Diaries of S. W. Jackson\", ''Emu'', 58 (1958), 75\u201376. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"J. R. Elsey, Surgeon, Naturalist, Explorer\", ''Queensland Naturalist'', 17 (3/4) (1964), 60\u201370. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Some Early Letters in Australian Ornithology\", ''Emu'', 63 (1964). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"J. R. Elsey, Explorer of the Never-Never\", ''Journal of the Royal Australian Historical Society'', 52 (1966). \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Dudley Dickison - Student of Birds and Books\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 84 (8) (1967), 251\u2013253. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Obituary. Gilbert Roscoe Gannon\", ''Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales'', 89 (1968), 12. \n* \u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014, \"Obituaries: Roy Percy Cooper\", ''Emu'', 77 (2) (1977), 88. \n==Journal articles about Alexander Chisholm==\n* McGill, A. R., \"Alexander Hugh Chisholm\", ''Emu'', 77 (1977), 232\u2013235. \n* Willis, J. H., \"Alexander Hugh Chisholm, OBE, CMZS., C.F.A.O.U. (1890\u20131977). An Appreciation\", ''Victorian Naturalist'', 94 (5) (1977), 188\u2013190.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Alec H. Chisholm in the [http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P001137b.htm ''Encyclopaedia of Australian Science'']\n*Biography in [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chisholm-alexander-hugh-alec-9741 ''The Australian Dictionary of Biography'']\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chisholm, Alexander Hugh}}\n[[Category:Australian ornithologists]]\n[[Category:Australian nature writers]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Australian naturalists]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Australian editors]]\n[[Category:Australian encyclopedists]]\n[[Category:Australian broadcasters]]\n", "name_user": "Oronsay", "label": "safe", "comment": "formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Hugh_Chisholm"}
{"title_page": "Keir Starmer", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{warning|image=Ambox_current_red.svg|heading=Warning!|This article is being heavily edited because of a recent election. Surrounding events may change rapidly as more facts come. Initial news reports may be unreliable, and the most recent updates to this article may not reflect the most current information. Please feel free to improve this article (but note that updates without valid and reliable references will be removed) or discuss changes on the talk page.}}\n{{short description|Leader of the UK Labour Party}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                = Sir Keir Starmer\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCB|QC|MP}}\n| image               = Official portrait of Keir Starmer crop 2.jpg\n| office               = [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| monarch              = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor          = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| successor            = \n| primeminister        = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start           = 4 April 2020\n| term_end             = \n| office1             = [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| term_start1         = 4 April 2020\n| term_end1           = \n| deputy1             = [[Angela Rayner]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2              = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n| leader2              = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2          = 6 October 2016\n| term_end2            = 4 April 2020\n| predecessor2         = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n| successor2           = Position abolished\n| office3             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2015\n| term_end3           = \n| predecessor3        = [[Frank Dobson]]\n| majority3           = 27,763 (48.9%)\n| office4             = [[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]]\n| term_start4         = 1 November 2008\n| term_end4           = 1 November 2013\n| predecessor4        = [[Ken Macdonald]]\n| successor4          = [[Alison Saunders]]\n|birth_name=Keir Rodney Starmer<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=t3VXAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Keir+Rodney+Starmer%22&dq=%22Keir+Rodney+Starmer%22 |title = Belize government gazette|year = 1997}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|9|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[Southwark]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Victoria Alexander|2007}}\n| children            = 2\n| education           = [[Reigate Grammar School]]\n| alma_mater          = {{Unbulleted list |[[University of Leeds]] ([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]]) |[[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]] ([[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]])}}\n| website             = {{official website|www.keirstarmer.com}}\n| caption             = Starmer in 2017\n| order               = \n| width               = \n| termend2            = \n}}\n{{Keir Starmer sidebar}}\n'''Sir Keir Rodney Starmer''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCB|QC}} (born 2 September 1962) is a British politician who has been [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]] since [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020]]. He has also been [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]] since [[UK general election, 2015|2015]].\n\nAfter qualifying for the [[Bar (law)|bar]], he acted exclusively as a [[Criminal defense lawyer|defence lawyer]] specialising in [[human rights]] issues, before being appointed as a [[Queen's Counsel]] (QC) in 2002. In 2008, he became [[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]] (DPP) and [[Crown Prosecution Service|Head of the Crown Prosecution Service]] (CPS), holding these roles until 2013. For his role as Director of Public Prosecutions he was appointed [[Order of the Bath|Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) in the [[2014 New Year Honours]].\n\nElected to the [[House of Commons]] in the [[UK general election, 2015|2015 general election]], Starmer was appointed by [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Home Office|Shadow Minister of State for Immigration]], a role from which [[Jeremy Corbyn#Shadow Cabinet resignations and vote of no confidence|Starmer resigned in 2016]], along with numerous other Labour MPs, in protest at Corbyn's leadership. Starmer was later appointed to the [[Shadow Cabinet]] in October 2016 as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]], after the [[Brexit|vote to leave]] the [[European Union]]. Starmer was a vocal advocate for a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]], stating he would have voted to remain. After Labour's defeat in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], Starmer was [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|elected]] as the new Leader of the Labour Party on 4 April 2020.\n\n==Early life and education==\nKeir Starmer was born in [[Southwark]], [[London]], on 2 September 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=x%2FPcgXTTczcfUM1dqszgrw&scan=1 |title=Index entry |accessdate=25 February 2018 |work=FreeBMD |publisher=ONS}}</ref> He was one of five children of Josephine ({{nee|Baker}}), a nurse, and Rodney Starmer, a [[toolmaker]]. His mother had [[Still's disease]].<ref name=guardian-20200327>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/27/keir-starmer-profile-labours-non-aligned-leadership-frontrunner |title=Keir Starmer had no enemies. Can he keep it that way? |last=Stewart |first=Heather |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.43670 |title=Starmer, Rt Hon. Sir Keir, (born 2 Sept. 1962), PC 2017; QC 2002; MP (Lab) Holborn and St Pancras, since 2015 |journal=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]] |year=2007}}</ref> Keir was named after the first [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP, [[Keir Hardie]].<ref name=\"Moss\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/sep/21/keir-starmer-director-public-prosecutions |location=London |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Stephen |last=Moss |title=Keir Starmer: 'I wouldn't characterise myself as a bleeding heart liberal . . .' |date=21 September 2009}}</ref> He passed the [[Eleven-plus|11-plus]] examination and gained entry to [[Reigate Grammar School]], then a [[Voluntary aided school|voluntary aided]] state school, although it converted to an independent fee-paying grammar school in 1976 while he was there.<ref name=\"Moss\" /> He studied law at the [[University of Leeds]], graduating with a [[first class honours|first class]] [[Bachelor of Laws]] (LLB) degree in 1985. He undertook [[postgraduate studies]] at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], graduating from the [[University of Oxford]] as a [[Bachelor of Civil Law]] (BCL) in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/23502/Keir-STARMER |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150223124824/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/23502/Keir-STARMER |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 February 2015 |title=People of Today |publisher=Debretts.com |date= |accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nStarmer became a [[barrister]] in 1987, at the [[Middle Temple]], later becoming a [[bencher]] there in 2009.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-43670 |title=Starmer, Rt Hon. Sir Keir, (born 2 Sept. 1962), PC 2017; QC 2002; MP (Lab) Holborn and St Pancras, since 2015 {{!}} WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO |website=www.ukwhoswho.com |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U43670|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> He was a member of [[Doughty Street Chambers]], primarily working on human rights issues.<ref name=guardian-20200327/> He has been [[Call to the bar|called to the bar]] in several Caribbean countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.middletemple.org.uk/bencher-persons-view?cid=32311 |title=Middle Temple |website=www.middletemple.org.uk |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> He notably worked for Helen Steel and David Morris in the [[McLibel case]], which went to court in 1997. In an interview, he described the case as \"very much a David and Goliath\", and said that \"there's an extremely good legal team acting for [[McDonald's]] at great expense and Dave and Helen have had to act for themselves with me as a sort of free back up whenever possible.\" He was interviewed for ''[[McLibel (film)|McLibel]]'', the documentary about the case directed by [[Franny Armstrong]] and [[Ken Loach]].<ref name=\"mclibel\">{{cite web |title=Keir Starmer interview |url=http://www.mcspotlight.org/people/interviews/starmer.html |website=McSpotlight |accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> \n\nHe was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] in 2002, the same year he became joint head of Doughty Street Chambers. Starmer also served as a human rights adviser to the [[Northern Ireland Policing Board]] and the [[Association of Chief Police Officers]], and was also a member of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] Death Penalty Advisory Panel from 2002 to 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2007, he was named \"QC of the Year\" by the UK legal directory.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/aug/01/humanrights.law?gusrc=rss&feed=worldnews Stephen Bates: \"Profile: Keir Starmer QC\"] (1 August 2008), ''The Guardian''</ref>\n\n===Director of Public Prosecutions===\nIn July 2008, [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] [[Patricia Scotland]] named Starmer as the new [[Crown Prosecution Service|Head of the Crown Prosecution Service]] and [[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]]; he took over from [[Ken Macdonald]] on 1 November 2008.<ref name=lawyer250708>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/aug/01/humanrights.law |title=Profile: Keir Starmer QC |first=Stephen |last=Bates |date=31 July 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> Macdonald, himself a former defence lawyer, publicly welcomed the appointment.<ref name=\"Moss\" />\n\nIn February 2009, Starmer approved a decision not to prosecute any police over the controversial shooting of [[Jean Charles de Menezes]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/family-of-jean-charles-de-menezes-1009708 | title=Family of Jean Charles de Menezes end battle for justice after DPP refuses to prosecute cops over shooting| date=14 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Starmer announced the decision not to prosecute the police officer Simon Harwood in relation to the [[death of Ian Tomlinson]]; this led to accusations by Tomlinson's family of a police cover-up.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/jul/22/ian-tomlinson-police-not-charged |location=London |work=The Guardian |title=Ian Tomlinson death: police officer will not face criminal charges |first1=Vikram |last1=Dodd |first2=Paul |last2=Lewis |date=22 July 2010 |access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> After a subsequent inquest found that Tomlinson had been unlawfully killed, Starmer announced that Harwood would be prosecuted for manslaughter. The officer was acquitted in July 2012, but dismissed from the police that September.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/may/24/dpp-statement-prosecute-simon-harwood |title=DPP's statement on the decision to prosecute Simon Harwood |date=24 May 2011 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Simon Harwood cleared of manslaughter |date=19 July 2012 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/jul/19/simon-harwood-not-guilty-ian-tomlinson |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/sep/17/simon-harwood-sacked-gross-misconduct |title=Ian Tomlinson case: PC Simon Harwood sacked for gross misconduct |last=Walker |first=Peter |date=17 September 2012 |work=The Guardian |access-date=22 December 2019 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Starmer announced that [[Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change|Energy Secretary]] [[Chris Huhne]] and his former wife, [[Vicky Pryce]], [[R v Huhne|would be prosecuted]] for [[perverting the course of justice]]. Huhne became the first [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet Minister]] in British history to be compelled to resign as a result of criminal proceedings.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Settle |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/political-news/huhne-forced-to-resign-as-points-court-battle-looms |title=Huhne forced to resign as points court battle looms |newspaper=The Herald |location= Glasgow |date=4 February 2012}}</ref> Starmer had previously said in relation to the case that \"[w]here there is sufficient evidence we do not shy away from prosecuting politicians\".<ref>Keir Starmer QC, [http://blog.cps.gov.uk/2011/11/letter-to-the-daily-mail-from-cps-about-chris-huhne.html \"Letter to the Daily Mail from CPS about the Chris Huhne case\"], ''The blog of the Crown Prosecution Service'', (23 November 2011)</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2012, journalist [[Nick Cohen]] published allegations that Starmer was personally responsible for allowing to proceed the prosecution of Paul Chambers in what became known as the \"[[Twitter Joke Trial]]\". Chambers\u2019 conviction of sending a message \"of a menacing character\" was quashed after a third appeal. The CPS denied that Starmer was behind the decision, saying that it was the responsibility of a Crown Court and was out of Starmer's hands.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Cohen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2012/jul/29/paul-chambers-twitter-joke-airport |title='Twitter joke' case only went ahead at insistence of DPP |work=The Observer |location=London |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=28 September 2015 |author-link=Nick Cohen}}</ref>\n\nStarmer left office in November 2013, and was replaced by [[Alison Saunders]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Branagh |first=Ellen |title=Stephen Lawrence barrister Alison Saunders to take over from Keir Starmer as new Director of Public Prosecutions |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/stephen-lawrence-barrister-alison-saunders-to-take-over-from-keir-starmer-as-new-director-of-public-prosecutions-8728313.html |accessdate=23 July 2013 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=23 July 2013 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saunders to replace Starmer at DPP |url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/uk-world-news/2013/07/23/saunders-to-replace-starmer-at-dpp-99623-33644921/ |accessdate=23 July 2013 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Daily Post]] |date=23 July 2013}}</ref> Later that month, the Labour Party announced that Starmer would lead an enquiry into changing the law to give further protection to victims in cases of rape and child abuse.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25528966 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |title=Keir Starmer heads Labour's victim treatment review |date=28 December 2013}}</ref> On 28 December, he said to [[BBC News]]: \"Well, I'm back in private practice; I'm rather enjoying having some free time, and I'm considering a number of options\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/90506/keir_starmer_victims_law_a_real_gear_change_to_justice_system.html |work=Politics Home |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214073337/https://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/90506/keir_starmer_victims_law_a_real_gear_change_to_justice_system.html |title=Keir Starmer: Victims' law a real gear change to justice system |archivedate=14 December 2014 |date=1 January 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nStarmer was selected in December 2014 to be the Labour Party's prospective parliamentary candidate for the [[constituency]] of [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]], following the decision of the sitting MP [[Frank Dobson]] to retire.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2014/dec/13/keir-starmer-stand-labour-mp-holborn-st-pancras |title=Keir Starmer to stand for Labour in Holborn and St Pancras |newspaper=The Guardian |date=13 December 2014}}</ref> Starmer was elected at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] with a majority of 17,048.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000750 |title=Holborn & St. Pancras Parliamentary Constituency |publisher=BBC News |date=8 May 2015}}</ref> He was urged by a number of activists to stand to be [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|leader of the Labour Party]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 leadership election]] following the resignation of [[Ed Miliband]], but he ruled this out, citing his relative lack of political experience.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/15/labour-activists-urge-keir-starmer-to-stand-for-party-leadership |title=Labour activists urge Keir Starmer to stand for party leadership |author=Matthew Weaver |date=15 May 2015 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=17 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Keir Starmer rules himself out of Labour leadership contest |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2015/may/17/keir-starmer-rules-himself-out-labour-leadership-contest |work=The Guardian |date=17 May 2015 |accessdate=17 May 2015 |author=Caroline Davies}}</ref> During the campaign, Keir Starmer supported [[Andy Burnham]], who finished second to [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news |title=Splits emerge as Jeremy Corbyn finalises Labour's shadow cabinet |last=Wilkinson |first=Michael |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11861535/jeremy-corbyn-picks-labour-shadow-cabinet-live.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 September 2015 |accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> \n\n===Shadow Cabinet===\nCorbyn appointed Starmer to the shadow Home Office ministerial team as [[Minister of State for Immigration|Shadow Minister of State for Immigration]], a role from which Starmer resigned in 2016 in protest at Corbyn's leadership, along with numerous other Labour MPs,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Keir-Starmer/4514 |title=Rt Hon Keir Starmer MP |author=UK Parliament |work=UK Parliament |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/update/2016-06-27/keir-starmer-resigns-as-shadow-home-office-minister/ |title=Keir Starmer resigns as shadow home office minister |publisher=ITV News|date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> arguing that it was \"simply untenable now to suggest we can offer an effective opposition without a change of leader\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/06/mps-vote-no-confidence-jeremy-corbyn-after-shadow-cabinet-revolt-it-happened |title = MPS vote no confidence in Jeremy Corbyn after shadow cabinet revolt: As it happened}}</ref> Following Corbyn's [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|re-election]] as leader in September 2016, Starmer accepted appointment as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|shadow Brexit secretary]], replacing [[Emily Thornberry]] in this role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.politicalbetting.com/index.php/archives/2016/10/06/jeremy-corbyn-has-appointed-sir-keir-starmer-as-shadow-brexit-secreretary-and-the-tories-should-be-worried/ |title=Jeremy Corbyn has appointed Sir Keir Starmer as Shadow Brexit Secretary and the Tories should be worried |date=6 October 2016 |website=politicalbetting.com |access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref> On taking up the role, Starmer resigned from a consultancy position with the law firm specialising in human rights, [[Mishcon de Reya]] LLP, that had acted for [[Gina Miller]] in bringing [[R (Miller and Dos Santos) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|legal proceedings against the Government]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Peter |title=Keir Starmer in talks for role with law firm that represented Gina Miller |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/24/keir-starmer-in-talks-for-role-with-law-firm-that-represented-gina-miller |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=24 July 2017 |access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his role as shadow Brexit secretary, Starmer questioned the Government's \"destination\" for the UK outside of the [[European Union]], as well as calling for Brexit plans to be made public. On 6 December 2016, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] confirmed the publication of such plans, in what some considered a victory for Starmer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38232780 |title=Labour says MPs are entitled to Brexit plan details |date=7 December 2016 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref> Starmer has argued that the Government would be subject to a race against time to pass a large number of new laws, or risk an \"unsustainable legal vacuum\", if Britain left the EU without a deal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/26/no-deal-brexit-uk-legal-vacuum-keir-starmer-theresa-may |title=No-deal Brexit thrusts UK into 'legal vacuum', warns Keir Starmer |last=Stewart |first=Heather |date=26 August 2018 |work=The Guardian |access-date=27 August 2018 |location=London}}</ref> On 25 September 2018, he declared to the [[2018 Labour Party Conference|Labour Party Conference]] in [[Liverpool]] that \"campaigning [by the party] for a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|public vote]] must be an option\".<ref name=\"Guardian_motion\">{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aP6w4tvzfFs |title='Nobody is ruling out remain as an option': Keir Starmer at Labour's Brexit debate |date=25 September 2018 |people=Keir Starmer, [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Shadow Brexit Secretary]] (speaker) |publisher=Guardian News via [[YouTube]] |access-date=25 September 2018 |medium=Television}}</ref>\n\nStarmer has called for a reform to the [[Freedom of movement for workers in the European Union|EU free movement rules]] following Brexit and for a \"fundamental rethink of immigration rules from start to finish\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-article-50-sir-keir-starmer-jeremy-corbyn-immigration-eu-free-movement-a7504331.html |title=Labour's Sir Keir Starmer says EU free movement rules 'have got to be changed' |date=2017-01-01 |website=The Independent |access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> In his first interview after being appointed to the Shadow Cabinet, Starmer argued that immigration was too high and called for it to be reduced as Britain leaves the EU, despite Corbyn ruling out any cap.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/oct/09/keir-starmer-calls-for-immigration-to-be-reduced |title=Keir Starmer calls for immigration to be reduced |last=Syal |first=Rajeev |date=2016-10-09 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-01-13 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Starmer told ''[[Politico]]'' in April 2016 that negotiations with the EU should start on the understanding that there must be \"some change\" to freedom of movement rules, given that remaining in the EU single market is no longer a reality.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/keir-starmer-britains-last-remaining-hope/ |title=Keir Starmer: Britain's last Remaining hope |date=2016-11-04 |website=POLITICO |access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2017, Starmer said that \"free movement has to go\", but that it was important to retain \"free movement of labour\", given the importance of immigration for the UK's economy.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/25/jeremy-corbyn-faces-new-split-immigration-keir-starmer-says/ |title=Labour's flagship vow to end free movement unravels as party says EU migrants with jobs can come to UK |last=Swinford |first=Steven |date=2017-04-25 |work=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=2020-01-13 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Starmer was a supporter of a second referendum on Brexit,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/07/keir-starmer-battles-to-keep-labour-support-for-peoples-vote-alive |title=Keir Starmer battles to keep Labour support for people's vote alive |date=2019-02-07 |website=The Guardian |access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> with this position becoming Labour Party policy in their 2019 General Election manifesto.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-49646544 |title=Brexit; Labour manifesto to offer vote on Leave and Remain |date=2019-09-10 |website=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 leadership election ===\n{{Main|2020 Labour Party leadership election}}\n[[File:Keir Starmer, 2020 Labour Party leadership election hustings, Bristol 3.jpg|thumb|Starmer speaking at the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]] hustings in Bristol]]\n\nFollowing Labour's heavy defeat in the [[2019 UK general election|2019 general election]], Jeremy Corbyn announced that he would stand down as Leader of the Labour Party. Starmer announced his candidacy in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|ensuing leadership election]] on 4 January 2020, winning multiple endorsements from MPs as well as from the trade union [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50995782 |title=Keir Starmer enters Labour leadership contest |date=4 January 2020 |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> He went on to win the leadership contest on 4 April 2020, having beaten rivals [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] and [[Lisa Nandy]] with 56.2% of the vote in the first round.<ref name=\"Labour Leader\"/>\n\n==Leader of the Opposition==\nOn 4 April 2020, Starmer was elected as leader of the Labour Party and thus [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589 |title=Keir Starmer Elected as new Labour leader |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> He was elected in the first round of voting with 275,780 votes (56.2%).<ref name=\"Labour Leader\">{{Cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/people/leadership-elections-hub-2020/leadership-elections-2020-results/|title=Leaderhip Elections 2020 Results|website=The Labour Party|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\nStarmer has been described as '[[soft left]]'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/21/keir-starmer-soft-left-approach-unifying-labour |title=Keir Starmer's soft-left approach is the unifying force that Labour needs |publisher=The Guardian |date=21 January 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |first=Zoe |last=Williams}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lawson |first1=Neal |title=Labour is at war with itself. What's needed? The soft left |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/04/labour-is-at-war-with-itself-the-missing-ingredient-is-the-soft-left/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[LabourList]] |date=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/keir-starmer-is-labour-s-continuity-miliband-contender |title=Keir Starmer is Labour's 'continuity Miliband' contender |publisher=The Spectator |date=22 January 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |first=Steven |last=Fielding}}</ref> He supports [[common ownership]] and investment in the UK's public services, including the [[NHS]], as well as the abolition of university tuition fees.<ref name=\"10 Pledges\">{{cite web|url=https://keirstarmer.com/plans/10-pledges/ |title=My Pledges to You |publisher=Keir Starmer.com |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"New European\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/keir-starmer-labour-leadership-right-to-take-radical-position-1-6444007 |title=Labour was 'right' to take 'radical' position on austerity, says Keir Starmer |publisher=The New European |date=30 December 2019 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/11/keir-starmer-calls-for-end-to-scandal-of-spiralling-student-debt |title= Keir Starmer calls for end to 'scandal' of spiralling student debt |publisher=The Guardian |date=11 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He has called for an increase in income tax for the top 5% of earners and an end to [[tax avoidance]] by corporations.<ref name=\"10 Pledges\"/> He advocates the reversal of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]'s cuts in corporation tax and supported Labour's anti-[[austerity]] proposals under Jeremy Corbyn's leadership.<ref name=\"10 Pledges\"/><ref name=\"New European\"/> On [[social inequality]], Starmer proposes \"national wellbeing indicators\" to measure the country's performance on health, inequality, homelessness, and the environment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cambridgeindependent.co.uk/news/sir-keir-starmer-pledges-to-prioritise-nation-s-wellbeing-on-cambridge-visit-9098870/ |title=Sir Keir Starmer pledges to prioritise nation's wellbeing on Cambridge visit |publisher=Cambridge Independent|date=6 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He has called for an \"overhaul\" of the UK's [[Universal Credit]] scheme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/keir-starmer-universal-credit-labour-leadership-domestic-abuse-bill-violence-a9322206.html |title=Keir Starmer demands overhaul of 'deeply flawed' universal credit to protect domestic abuse survivors |publisher=The Independent|date=6 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of [[foreign policy]], Starmer has advocated for an end to \"illegal wars\" and a review of the [[UK arms export|United Kingdom's arms sales]].<ref name=\"10 Pledges\"/> During his leadership campaign, he pledged to create a \"Prevention of Military Intervention Act\", which would only permit lawful military action with the support of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-election-keir-starmer-long-bailey-nandy-voting-record-policy-compare-a9356741.html |title=Labour leadership: The key policies of Keir Starmer, Rebecca Long-Bailey and Lisa Nandy |publisher=The Independent |date=25 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PMIA\">{{cite web |url=https://labourlist.org/2020/02/what-does-keir-starmer-mean-by-a-prevention-of-military-intervention-act/ |title=What does Keir Starmer mean by a 'Prevention of Military Intervention Act'? |website=LabourList |date=12 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> Starmer had previously opposed the [[Iraq War]], stating that it was \"not lawful under international law because there was no [[United Nations|UN]] resolution expressly authorising it.\"<ref name=\"PMIA\"/>\n\nStarmer has been criticised for his opposition to [[Brexit]], with some Labour colleagues citing his support for a second referendum as a reason the party lost the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]].<ref name=\"Guardian Brexit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/16/labour-leadership-contest-keir-starmer-defends-brexit-policy |title=Labour leadership contest: Keir Starmer defends Brexit policy  |publisher=The Guardian |date=16 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> In response, Starmer reiterated his belief in his position.<ref name=\"Guardian Brexit\"/> \n\n== Personal life ==\nStarmer married Victoria Alexander, a Jewish [[solicitor]], in 2007, and has a son and daughter, who are being brought up in the Jewish faith.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/><ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/keir-starmer-elected-uk-labour-chief-apologizes-to-jews-for-party-anti-semitism/ After Corbyn, UK Labour elects Keir Starmer, Zionist with Jewish wife, as leader]</ref> He was awarded a knighthood in 2014 for \"services to law and criminal justice\" and is entitled \"Sir Keir Starmer\". He prefers not to be called Sir.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pickard |first=Jim |date=17 October 2016 |title=Keir Starmer: the Brexit opponent making Labour heard on Europe |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a4b98018-9225-11e6-8df8-d3778b55a923 |work=[[Financial Times]] |location=London |access-date=23 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lamden |first=Tim |date=27 March 2015 |title=Keir Starmer: 'My mum's health battles have inspired me' |url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/sir-keir-starmer-my-mum-s-health-battles-have-inspired-me-1-4011167 |work=[[Hampstead & Highgate Express]] |location=London |access-date=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n[[File:Order of the Bath knight commander civil division star (United Kingdom after 1950) - Tallinn Museum of Orders.jpg|right|150px]]\n* Appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] (QC) in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/L-56538-1002 |title=Crown Office |website=www.thegazette.co.uk |access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Bar Council's Sydney Elland Goldsmith Award in 2005, for his outstanding contribution to ''[[pro bono]]'' work in challenging the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.awardsintelligence.co.uk/awards/knighthood-former-director-of-public-prosecutions-keir-starmer-qc/ |title=Knighthood: former Director of Public Prosecutions Keir Starmer QC |date=2 January 2014 |website=awards intelligence}}</ref>\n* Appointed [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) in the [[2014 New Year Honours]] for \"services to law and criminal justice\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60728 |supp=y |page=3 |date=31 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/268845/New_Year_Honours_2014_notes_on_higher_awards.pdf |title=The New Year Honours List 2014 \u2013 Higher Awards |date=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n* Sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] on 19 July 2017.<ref name=\"privycouncil.independent.gov.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/2017-07-19-List-of-Business-Part-1.pdf |title=Business Transacted and Orders Approved at The Privy Council Held by The Queen at Buckingham Palace on 19th July 2017 |access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n* Elected [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Fellow]] of [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/people/keir-starmer |title=Keir Starmer - Honorary Fellow |website=St Edmund Hall |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honorary degrees==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! School !! Degree\n|-\n| 21 July 2011\n| [[University of Essex]]\n| [[Honorary degree|Doctor of University]] (D.U.)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essex.ac.uk/honorary_graduates/ |title=Honorary Graduates - Profile: Keir Starmer QC |publisher=University of Essex |date= |accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 16 July 2012\n| [[University of Leeds]]\n| [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/130509/honorary_graduates |title=Honorary graduates |first=Tanya |last=O'Rourke |website=www.leeds.ac.uk |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 19 November 2013\n| [[University of East London]]\n| [[Honorary degree|Doctor of University]] (D.U.)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newhamrecorder.co.uk/news/education/keir-starmer-qc-awarded-honorary-doctorate-by-east-london-university-1-3016174 |title=Keir Starmer QC, awarded honorary doctorate by east London university |first=Kay |last=Atwal |website=Newham Recorder |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 19 December 2013 \n| [[London School of Economics]]\n| [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/intranet/LSEServices/governanceAndCommittees/lse_honorary_degrees.aspx |title=LSE Honorary Degrees |first=Dan |last=Bennett |website=www.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/website-archive/newsAndMedia/newsArchives/2013/12/KeirStarmer.aspx |title=Keir Starmer QC awarded an LSE Honorary Degree |website=www.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 14 July 2014\n| [[University of Reading]]\n| [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reading.ac.uk/news-and-events/releases/PR589467.aspx |date=14 July 2014 |title=Leading legal figure awarded Honorary Degree |publisher=University of Reading |access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 18 November 2014\n| [[University of Worcester]]\n| [[Honorary degree|Doctor of University]] (D.U.)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.worcester.ac.uk/community/sir-keir-starmer-kcb-qc-graduation-2014.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116001126/https://www.worcester.ac.uk/community/sir-keir-starmer-kcb-qc-graduation-2014.html |archive-date=16 November 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Publications ==\nStarmer is the author and editor of several books about criminal law and human rights:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* ''Justice in error'', ed. by Clive Walker and Keir Starmer (London: Blackstone, 1993), {{ISBN|1-85431-234-0}}\n* Francesca Klug, Keir Starmer and Stuart Weir, ''The three pillars of liberty: political rights and freedoms in the United Kingdom'' (London: Routledge, 1996), {{ISBN|0-415-09641-3}}\n* Conor Foley and Keir Starmer, ''Signing up for human rights: the United Kingdom and international standards'' (London: Amnesty International United Kingdom, 1998), {{ISBN|1-873328-30-3}}\n* ''Miscarriages of justice: a review of justice in error'', ed. by Clive Walker and Keir Starmer (London: Blackstone, 1999), {{ISBN|1-85431-687-7}}\n* Keir Starmer, ''European human rights law: the Human Rights Act 1998 and the European Convention on Human Rights'' (London: Legal Action Group, 1999), {{ISBN|0-905099-77-X}}\n* Keir Starmer, Michelle Strange, and Quincy Whitaker, with Anthony Jennings and Tim Owen, ''Criminal justice, police powers and human rights'' (London: Blackstone, 2001), {{ISBN|1-84174-138-8}}\n* Keir Starmer with Iain Byrne, ''Blackstone's human rights digest'' (London: Blackstone, 2001), {{ISBN|1-84174-153-1}}\n* Keir Starmer and Jane Gordon, ''A report on the policing of the Ardoyne parades 12 July 2004'' (Belfast: Northern Ireland Policing Board, 2004)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|www.keirstarmer.com}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=keir-starmer/4514 |publicwhip=Keir_Starmer |theywork=keir_starmer}}\n*[http://www.cps.gov.uk/about/dpp.html CPS]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ken Macdonald]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]]|years=2008\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alison Saunders]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Dobson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Emily Thornberry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=Office Abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Corbyn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Corbyn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Leaders of the Opposition UK}}\n{{Shadow Great Officers of State}}\n{{Leaders of political parties in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2020}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starmer, Keir}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Reigate Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Directors of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Lawyers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Kentish Town]]\n[[Category:People from Reigate]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 2001\u2013]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Labour Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (United Kingdom)]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{warning|image=Ambox_current_red.svg|heading=Warning!|This article is being heavily edited because of a recent election. Surrounding events may change rapidly as more facts come. Initial news reports may be unreliable, and the most recent updates to this article may not reflect the most current information. Please feel free to improve this article (but note that updates without valid and reliable references will be removed) or discuss changes on the talk page.}}\n{{short description|Leader of the UK Labour Party}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                = Sir Keir Starmer\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCB|QC|MP}}\n| image               = Official portrait of Keir Starmer crop 2.jpg\n| office               = [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| monarch              = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor          = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| successor            = \n| primeminister        = [[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start           = 4 April 2020\n| term_end             = \n| office1             = [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| term_start1         = 4 April 2020\n| term_end1           = \n| deputy1             = [[Angela Rayner]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| successor1          = \n| office2              = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]\n| leader2              = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n| term_start2          = 6 October 2016\n| term_end2            = 4 April 2020\n| predecessor2         = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n| successor2           = Position abolished\n| office3             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]]\n| term_start3         = 7 May 2015\n| term_end3           = \n| predecessor3        = [[Frank Dobson]]\n| majority3           = 27,763 (48.9%)\n| office4             = [[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]]\n| term_start4         = 1 November 2008\n| term_end4           = 1 November 2013\n| predecessor4        = [[Ken Macdonald]]\n| successor4          = [[Alison Saunders]]\n|birth_name=Keir Rodney Starmer<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/?id=t3VXAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Keir+Rodney+Starmer%22&dq=%22Keir+Rodney+Starmer%22 |title = Belize government gazette|year = 1997}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1962|9|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[Southwark]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Victoria Alexander|2007}}\n| children            = 2\n| education           = [[Reigate Grammar School]]\n| alma_mater          = {{Unbulleted list |[[University of Leeds]] ([[Bachelor of Laws|LLB]]) |[[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]] ([[Bachelor of Civil Law|BCL]])}}\n| website             = {{official website|www.keirstarmer.com}}\n| caption             = Starmer in 2017\n| order               = \n| width               = \n| termend2            = \n}}\n{{Keir Starmer sidebar}}\n'''Sir Keir Rodney Starmer''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCB|QC}} (born 2 September 1962) is a British politician who has been [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]] since [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|2020]]. He has also been [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]] since [[UK general election, 2015|2015]].\n\nAfter qualifying for the [[Bar (law)|bar]], he acted exclusively as a [[Criminal defense lawyer|defence lawyer]] specialising in [[human rights]] issues, before being appointed as a [[Queen's Counsel]] (QC) in 2002. In 2008, he became [[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]] (DPP) and [[Crown Prosecution Service|Head of the Crown Prosecution Service]] (CPS), holding these roles until 2013. For his role as Director of Public Prosecutions he was appointed [[Order of the Bath|Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) in the [[2014 New Year Honours]].\n\nElected to the [[House of Commons]] in the [[UK general election, 2015|2015 general election]], Starmer was appointed by [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as [[Home Office|Shadow Minister of State for Immigration]], a role from which [[Jeremy Corbyn#Shadow Cabinet resignations and vote of no confidence|Starmer resigned in 2016]] in protest at Corbyn's leadership, along with numerous other Labour MPs. Starmer was later appointed to the [[Shadow Cabinet]] in October 2016 as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]], after the [[Brexit|vote to leave]] the [[European Union]]. Starmer was a vocal advocate for a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]], stating he would have voted to remain. After Labour's defeat in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], Starmer was [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|elected]] as the new Leader of the Labour Party on 4 April 2020.\n\n==Early life and education==\nKeir Starmer was born in [[Southwark]], [[London]], on 2 September 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=x%2FPcgXTTczcfUM1dqszgrw&scan=1 |title=Index entry |accessdate=25 February 2018 |work=FreeBMD |publisher=ONS}}</ref> He was one of five children of Josephine ({{nee|Baker}}), a nurse, and Rodney Starmer, a [[toolmaker]]. His mother had [[Still's disease]].<ref name=guardian-20200327>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/27/keir-starmer-profile-labours-non-aligned-leadership-frontrunner |title=Keir Starmer had no enemies. Can he keep it that way? |last=Stewart |first=Heather |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 March 2020 |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Who's Who\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.43670 |title=Starmer, Rt Hon. Sir Keir, (born 2 Sept. 1962), PC 2017; QC 2002; MP (Lab) Holborn and St Pancras, since 2015 |journal=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]] |year=2007}}</ref> Keir was named after the first [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] MP, [[Keir Hardie]].<ref name=\"Moss\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/2009/sep/21/keir-starmer-director-public-prosecutions |location=London |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Stephen |last=Moss |title=Keir Starmer: 'I wouldn't characterise myself as a bleeding heart liberal . . .' |date=21 September 2009}}</ref> He passed the [[Eleven-plus|11-plus]] examination and gained entry to [[Reigate Grammar School]], then a [[Voluntary aided school|voluntary aided]] state school, although it converted to an independent fee-paying grammar school in 1976 while he was there.<ref name=\"Moss\" /> He studied law at the [[University of Leeds]], graduating with a [[first class honours|first class]] [[Bachelor of Laws]] (LLB) degree in 1985. He undertook [[postgraduate studies]] at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], graduating from the [[University of Oxford]] as a [[Bachelor of Civil Law]] (BCL) in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/23502/Keir-STARMER |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150223124824/http://www.debretts.com/people-of-today/profile/23502/Keir-STARMER |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 February 2015 |title=People of Today |publisher=Debretts.com |date= |accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nStarmer became a [[barrister]] in 1987, at the [[Middle Temple]], later becoming a [[bencher]] there in 2009.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-43670 |title=Starmer, Rt Hon. Sir Keir, (born 2 Sept. 1962), PC 2017; QC 2002; MP (Lab) Holborn and St Pancras, since 2015 {{!}} WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO |website=www.ukwhoswho.com |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U43670|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> He was a member of [[Doughty Street Chambers]], primarily working on human rights issues.<ref name=guardian-20200327/> He has been [[Call to the bar|called to the bar]] in several Caribbean countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.middletemple.org.uk/bencher-persons-view?cid=32311 |title=Middle Temple |website=www.middletemple.org.uk |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> He notably worked for Helen Steel and David Morris in the [[McLibel case]], which went to court in 1997. In an interview, he described the case as \"very much a David and Goliath\", and said that \"there's an extremely good legal team acting for [[McDonald's]] at great expense and Dave and Helen have had to act for themselves with me as a sort of free back up whenever possible.\" He was interviewed for ''[[McLibel (film)|McLibel]]'', the documentary about the case directed by [[Franny Armstrong]] and [[Ken Loach]].<ref name=\"mclibel\">{{cite web |title=Keir Starmer interview |url=http://www.mcspotlight.org/people/interviews/starmer.html |website=McSpotlight |accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> \n\nHe was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] in 2002, the same year he became joint head of Doughty Street Chambers. Starmer also served as a human rights adviser to the [[Northern Ireland Policing Board]] and the [[Association of Chief Police Officers]], and was also a member of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]] Death Penalty Advisory Panel from 2002 to 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2007, he was named \"QC of the Year\" by the UK legal directory.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/aug/01/humanrights.law?gusrc=rss&feed=worldnews Stephen Bates: \"Profile: Keir Starmer QC\"] (1 August 2008), ''The Guardian''</ref>\n\n===Director of Public Prosecutions===\nIn July 2008, [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] [[Patricia Scotland]] named Starmer as the new [[Crown Prosecution Service|Head of the Crown Prosecution Service]] and [[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]]; he took over from [[Ken Macdonald]] on 1 November 2008.<ref name=lawyer250708>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/aug/01/humanrights.law |title=Profile: Keir Starmer QC |first=Stephen |last=Bates |date=31 July 2008 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> Macdonald, himself a former defence lawyer, publicly welcomed the appointment.<ref name=\"Moss\" />\n\nIn February 2009, Starmer approved a decision not to prosecute any police over the controversial shooting of [[Jean Charles de Menezes]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/family-of-jean-charles-de-menezes-1009708 | title=Family of Jean Charles de Menezes end battle for justice after DPP refuses to prosecute cops over shooting| date=14 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Starmer announced the decision not to prosecute the police officer Simon Harwood in relation to the [[death of Ian Tomlinson]]; this led to accusations by Tomlinson's family of a police cover-up.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/jul/22/ian-tomlinson-police-not-charged |location=London |work=The Guardian |title=Ian Tomlinson death: police officer will not face criminal charges |first1=Vikram |last1=Dodd |first2=Paul |last2=Lewis |date=22 July 2010 |access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> After a subsequent inquest found that Tomlinson had been unlawfully killed, Starmer announced that Harwood would be prosecuted for manslaughter. The officer was acquitted in July 2012, but dismissed from the police that September.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/may/24/dpp-statement-prosecute-simon-harwood |title=DPP's statement on the decision to prosecute Simon Harwood |date=24 May 2011 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Simon Harwood cleared of manslaughter |date=19 July 2012 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/jul/19/simon-harwood-not-guilty-ian-tomlinson |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=22 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/sep/17/simon-harwood-sacked-gross-misconduct |title=Ian Tomlinson case: PC Simon Harwood sacked for gross misconduct |last=Walker |first=Peter |date=17 September 2012 |work=The Guardian |access-date=22 December 2019 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Starmer announced that [[Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change|Energy Secretary]] [[Chris Huhne]] and his former wife, [[Vicky Pryce]], [[R v Huhne|would be prosecuted]] for [[perverting the course of justice]]. Huhne became the first [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet Minister]] in British history to be compelled to resign as a result of criminal proceedings.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Settle |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/political-news/huhne-forced-to-resign-as-points-court-battle-looms |title=Huhne forced to resign as points court battle looms |newspaper=The Herald |location= Glasgow |date=4 February 2012}}</ref> Starmer had previously said in relation to the case that \"[w]here there is sufficient evidence we do not shy away from prosecuting politicians\".<ref>Keir Starmer QC, [http://blog.cps.gov.uk/2011/11/letter-to-the-daily-mail-from-cps-about-chris-huhne.html \"Letter to the Daily Mail from CPS about the Chris Huhne case\"], ''The blog of the Crown Prosecution Service'', (23 November 2011)</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2012, journalist [[Nick Cohen]] published allegations that Starmer was personally responsible for allowing to proceed the prosecution of Paul Chambers in what became known as the \"[[Twitter Joke Trial]]\". Chambers\u2019 conviction of sending a message \"of a menacing character\" was quashed after a third appeal. The CPS denied that Starmer was behind the decision, saying that it was the responsibility of a Crown Court and was out of Starmer's hands.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Cohen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2012/jul/29/paul-chambers-twitter-joke-airport |title='Twitter joke' case only went ahead at insistence of DPP |work=The Observer |location=London |date=29 July 2012 |accessdate=28 September 2015 |author-link=Nick Cohen}}</ref>\n\nStarmer left office in November 2013, and was replaced by [[Alison Saunders]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Branagh |first=Ellen |title=Stephen Lawrence barrister Alison Saunders to take over from Keir Starmer as new Director of Public Prosecutions |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/stephen-lawrence-barrister-alison-saunders-to-take-over-from-keir-starmer-as-new-director-of-public-prosecutions-8728313.html |accessdate=23 July 2013 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=23 July 2013 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Saunders to replace Starmer at DPP |url=http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/uk-world-news/2013/07/23/saunders-to-replace-starmer-at-dpp-99623-33644921/ |accessdate=23 July 2013 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Daily Post]] |date=23 July 2013}}</ref> Later that month, the Labour Party announced that Starmer would lead an enquiry into changing the law to give further protection to victims in cases of rape and child abuse.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25528966 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |title=Keir Starmer heads Labour's victim treatment review |date=28 December 2013}}</ref> On 28 December, he said to [[BBC News]]: \"Well, I'm back in private practice; I'm rather enjoying having some free time, and I'm considering a number of options\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/90506/keir_starmer_victims_law_a_real_gear_change_to_justice_system.html |work=Politics Home |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214073337/https://www.politicshome.com/uk/article/90506/keir_starmer_victims_law_a_real_gear_change_to_justice_system.html |title=Keir Starmer: Victims' law a real gear change to justice system |archivedate=14 December 2014 |date=1 January 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\nStarmer was selected in December 2014 to be the Labour Party's prospective parliamentary candidate for the [[constituency]] of [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]], following the decision of the sitting MP [[Frank Dobson]] to retire.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2014/dec/13/keir-starmer-stand-labour-mp-holborn-st-pancras |title=Keir Starmer to stand for Labour in Holborn and St Pancras |newspaper=The Guardian |date=13 December 2014}}</ref> Starmer was elected at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] with a majority of 17,048.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000750 |title=Holborn & St. Pancras Parliamentary Constituency |publisher=BBC News |date=8 May 2015}}</ref> He was urged by a number of activists to stand to be [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|leader of the Labour Party]] in the [[2015 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2015 leadership election]] following the resignation of [[Ed Miliband]], but he ruled this out, citing his relative lack of political experience.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/15/labour-activists-urge-keir-starmer-to-stand-for-party-leadership |title=Labour activists urge Keir Starmer to stand for party leadership |author=Matthew Weaver |date=15 May 2015 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=17 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Keir Starmer rules himself out of Labour leadership contest |url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2015/may/17/keir-starmer-rules-himself-out-labour-leadership-contest |work=The Guardian |date=17 May 2015 |accessdate=17 May 2015 |author=Caroline Davies}}</ref> During the campaign, Keir Starmer supported [[Andy Burnham]], who finished second to [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news |title=Splits emerge as Jeremy Corbyn finalises Labour's shadow cabinet |last=Wilkinson |first=Michael |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/Jeremy_Corbyn/11861535/jeremy-corbyn-picks-labour-shadow-cabinet-live.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 September 2015 |accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref> \n\n===Shadow Cabinet===\nCorbyn appointed Starmer to the shadow Home Office ministerial team as [[Minister of State for Immigration|Shadow Minister of State for Immigration]], a role from which Starmer resigned in 2016 in protest at Corbyn's leadership, along with numerous other Labour MPs,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/Keir-Starmer/4514 |title=Rt Hon Keir Starmer MP |author=UK Parliament |work=UK Parliament |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/update/2016-06-27/keir-starmer-resigns-as-shadow-home-office-minister/ |title=Keir Starmer resigns as shadow home office minister |publisher=ITV News|date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> arguing that it was \"simply untenable now to suggest we can offer an effective opposition without a change of leader\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/06/mps-vote-no-confidence-jeremy-corbyn-after-shadow-cabinet-revolt-it-happened |title = MPS vote no confidence in Jeremy Corbyn after shadow cabinet revolt: As it happened}}</ref> Following Corbyn's [[2016 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|re-election]] as leader in September 2016, Starmer accepted appointment as [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|shadow Brexit secretary]], replacing [[Emily Thornberry]] in this role.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.politicalbetting.com/index.php/archives/2016/10/06/jeremy-corbyn-has-appointed-sir-keir-starmer-as-shadow-brexit-secreretary-and-the-tories-should-be-worried/ |title=Jeremy Corbyn has appointed Sir Keir Starmer as Shadow Brexit Secretary and the Tories should be worried |date=6 October 2016 |website=politicalbetting.com |access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref> On taking up the role, Starmer resigned from a consultancy position with the law firm specialising in human rights, [[Mishcon de Reya]] LLP, that had acted for [[Gina Miller]] in bringing [[R (Miller and Dos Santos) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|legal proceedings against the Government]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Peter |title=Keir Starmer in talks for role with law firm that represented Gina Miller |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/24/keir-starmer-in-talks-for-role-with-law-firm-that-represented-gina-miller |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=24 July 2017 |access-date=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his role as shadow Brexit secretary, Starmer questioned the Government's \"destination\" for the UK outside of the [[European Union]], as well as calling for Brexit plans to be made public. On 6 December 2016, Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] confirmed the publication of such plans, in what some considered a victory for Starmer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38232780 |title=Labour says MPs are entitled to Brexit plan details |date=7 December 2016 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref> Starmer has argued that the Government would be subject to a race against time to pass a large number of new laws, or risk an \"unsustainable legal vacuum\", if Britain left the EU without a deal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/26/no-deal-brexit-uk-legal-vacuum-keir-starmer-theresa-may |title=No-deal Brexit thrusts UK into 'legal vacuum', warns Keir Starmer |last=Stewart |first=Heather |date=26 August 2018 |work=The Guardian |access-date=27 August 2018 |location=London}}</ref> On 25 September 2018, he declared to the [[2018 Labour Party Conference|Labour Party Conference]] in [[Liverpool]] that \"campaigning [by the party] for a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|public vote]] must be an option\".<ref name=\"Guardian_motion\">{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aP6w4tvzfFs |title='Nobody is ruling out remain as an option': Keir Starmer at Labour's Brexit debate |date=25 September 2018 |people=Keir Starmer, [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|Shadow Brexit Secretary]] (speaker) |publisher=Guardian News via [[YouTube]] |access-date=25 September 2018 |medium=Television}}</ref>\n\nStarmer has called for a reform to the [[Freedom of movement for workers in the European Union|EU free movement rules]] following Brexit and for a \"fundamental rethink of immigration rules from start to finish\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-article-50-sir-keir-starmer-jeremy-corbyn-immigration-eu-free-movement-a7504331.html |title=Labour's Sir Keir Starmer says EU free movement rules 'have got to be changed' |date=2017-01-01 |website=The Independent |access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> In his first interview after being appointed to the Shadow Cabinet, Starmer argued that immigration was too high and called for it to be reduced as Britain leaves the EU, despite Corbyn ruling out any cap.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/oct/09/keir-starmer-calls-for-immigration-to-be-reduced |title=Keir Starmer calls for immigration to be reduced |last=Syal |first=Rajeev |date=2016-10-09 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-01-13 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Starmer told ''[[Politico]]'' in April 2016 that negotiations with the EU should start on the understanding that there must be \"some change\" to freedom of movement rules, given that remaining in the EU single market is no longer a reality.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/keir-starmer-britains-last-remaining-hope/ |title=Keir Starmer: Britain's last Remaining hope |date=2016-11-04 |website=POLITICO |access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> \n\nIn May 2017, Starmer said that \"free movement has to go\", but that it was important to retain \"free movement of labour\", given the importance of immigration for the UK's economy.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/04/25/jeremy-corbyn-faces-new-split-immigration-keir-starmer-says/ |title=Labour's flagship vow to end free movement unravels as party says EU migrants with jobs can come to UK |last=Swinford |first=Steven |date=2017-04-25 |work=The Daily Telegraph |access-date=2020-01-13 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Starmer was a supporter of a second referendum on Brexit,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/feb/07/keir-starmer-battles-to-keep-labour-support-for-peoples-vote-alive |title=Keir Starmer battles to keep Labour support for people's vote alive |date=2019-02-07 |website=The Guardian |access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> with this position becoming Labour Party policy in their 2019 General Election manifesto.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-49646544 |title=Brexit; Labour manifesto to offer vote on Leave and Remain |date=2019-09-10 |website=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 leadership election ===\n{{Main|2020 Labour Party leadership election}}\n[[File:Keir Starmer, 2020 Labour Party leadership election hustings, Bristol 3.jpg|thumb|Starmer speaking at the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]] hustings in Bristol]]\n\nFollowing Labour's heavy defeat in the [[2019 UK general election|2019 general election]], Jeremy Corbyn announced that he would stand down as Leader of the Labour Party. Starmer announced his candidacy in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election|ensuing leadership election]] on 4 January 2020, winning multiple endorsements from MPs as well as from the trade union [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-50995782 |title=Keir Starmer enters Labour leadership contest |date=4 January 2020 |access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref> He went on to win the leadership contest on 4 April 2020, having beaten rivals [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] and [[Lisa Nandy]] with 56.2% of the vote in the first round.<ref name=\"Labour Leader\"/>\n\n==Leader of the Opposition==\nOn 4 April 2020, Starmer was elected as leader of the Labour Party and thus [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589 |title=Keir Starmer Elected as new Labour leader |date=4 April 2020 |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> He was elected in the first round of voting with 275,780 votes (56.2%).<ref name=\"Labour Leader\">{{Cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/people/leadership-elections-hub-2020/leadership-elections-2020-results/|title=Leaderhip Elections 2020 Results|website=The Labour Party|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\nStarmer has been described as '[[soft left]]'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/jan/21/keir-starmer-soft-left-approach-unifying-labour |title=Keir Starmer's soft-left approach is the unifying force that Labour needs |publisher=The Guardian |date=21 January 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |first=Zoe |last=Williams}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lawson |first1=Neal |title=Labour is at war with itself. What's needed? The soft left |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/04/labour-is-at-war-with-itself-the-missing-ingredient-is-the-soft-left/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[LabourList]] |date=4 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/keir-starmer-is-labour-s-continuity-miliband-contender |title=Keir Starmer is Labour's 'continuity Miliband' contender |publisher=The Spectator |date=22 January 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |first=Steven |last=Fielding}}</ref> He supports [[common ownership]] and investment in the UK's public services, including the [[NHS]], as well as the abolition of university tuition fees.<ref name=\"10 Pledges\">{{cite web|url=https://keirstarmer.com/plans/10-pledges/ |title=My Pledges to You |publisher=Keir Starmer.com |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"New European\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/keir-starmer-labour-leadership-right-to-take-radical-position-1-6444007 |title=Labour was 'right' to take 'radical' position on austerity, says Keir Starmer |publisher=The New European |date=30 December 2019 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/11/keir-starmer-calls-for-end-to-scandal-of-spiralling-student-debt |title= Keir Starmer calls for end to 'scandal' of spiralling student debt |publisher=The Guardian |date=11 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He has called for an increase in income tax for the top 5% of earners and an end to [[tax avoidance]] by corporations.<ref name=\"10 Pledges\"/> He advocates the reversal of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]'s cuts in corporation tax and supported Labour's anti-[[austerity]] proposals under Jeremy Corbyn's leadership.<ref name=\"10 Pledges\"/><ref name=\"New European\"/> On [[social inequality]], Starmer proposes \"national wellbeing indicators\" to measure the country's performance on health, inequality, homelessness, and the environment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cambridgeindependent.co.uk/news/sir-keir-starmer-pledges-to-prioritise-nation-s-wellbeing-on-cambridge-visit-9098870/ |title=Sir Keir Starmer pledges to prioritise nation's wellbeing on Cambridge visit |publisher=Cambridge Independent|date=6 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He has called for an \"overhaul\" of the UK's [[Universal Credit]] scheme.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/keir-starmer-universal-credit-labour-leadership-domestic-abuse-bill-violence-a9322206.html |title=Keir Starmer demands overhaul of 'deeply flawed' universal credit to protect domestic abuse survivors |publisher=The Independent|date=6 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of [[foreign policy]], Starmer has advocated for an end to \"illegal wars\" and a review of the [[UK arms export|United Kingdom's arms sales]].<ref name=\"10 Pledges\"/> During his leadership campaign, he pledged to create a \"Prevention of Military Intervention Act\", which would only permit lawful military action with the support of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-leadership-election-keir-starmer-long-bailey-nandy-voting-record-policy-compare-a9356741.html |title=Labour leadership: The key policies of Keir Starmer, Rebecca Long-Bailey and Lisa Nandy |publisher=The Independent |date=25 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PMIA\">{{cite web |url=https://labourlist.org/2020/02/what-does-keir-starmer-mean-by-a-prevention-of-military-intervention-act/ |title=What does Keir Starmer mean by a 'Prevention of Military Intervention Act'? |website=LabourList |date=12 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> Starmer had previously opposed the [[Iraq War]], stating that it was \"not lawful under international law because there was no [[United Nations|UN]] resolution expressly authorising it.\"<ref name=\"PMIA\"/>\n\nStarmer has been criticised for his opposition to [[Brexit]], with some Labour colleagues citing his support for a second referendum as a reason the party lost the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]].<ref name=\"Guardian Brexit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/feb/16/labour-leadership-contest-keir-starmer-defends-brexit-policy |title=Labour leadership contest: Keir Starmer defends Brexit policy  |publisher=The Guardian |date=16 February 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> In response, Starmer reiterated his belief in his position.<ref name=\"Guardian Brexit\"/> \n\n== Personal life ==\nStarmer married Victoria Alexander, a Jewish [[solicitor]], in 2007, and has a son and daughter, who are being brought up in the Jewish faith.<ref name=\"Who's Who\"/><ref>[https://www.timesofisrael.com/keir-starmer-elected-uk-labour-chief-apologizes-to-jews-for-party-anti-semitism/ After Corbyn, UK Labour elects Keir Starmer, Zionist with Jewish wife, as leader]</ref> He was awarded a knighthood in 2014 for \"services to law and criminal justice\" and is entitled \"Sir Keir Starmer\". He prefers not to be called Sir.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pickard |first=Jim |date=17 October 2016 |title=Keir Starmer: the Brexit opponent making Labour heard on Europe |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a4b98018-9225-11e6-8df8-d3778b55a923 |work=[[Financial Times]] |location=London |access-date=23 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lamden |first=Tim |date=27 March 2015 |title=Keir Starmer: 'My mum's health battles have inspired me' |url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/seasonal/election/sir-keir-starmer-my-mum-s-health-battles-have-inspired-me-1-4011167 |work=[[Hampstead & Highgate Express]] |location=London |access-date=23 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n[[File:Order of the Bath knight commander civil division star (United Kingdom after 1950) - Tallinn Museum of Orders.jpg|right|150px]]\n* Appointed [[Queen's Counsel]] (QC) in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/L-56538-1002 |title=Crown Office |website=www.thegazette.co.uk |access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Bar Council's Sydney Elland Goldsmith Award in 2005, for his outstanding contribution to ''[[pro bono]]'' work in challenging the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.awardsintelligence.co.uk/awards/knighthood-former-director-of-public-prosecutions-keir-starmer-qc/ |title=Knighthood: former Director of Public Prosecutions Keir Starmer QC |date=2 January 2014 |website=awards intelligence}}</ref>\n* Appointed [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) in the [[2014 New Year Honours]] for \"services to law and criminal justice\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60728 |supp=y |page=3 |date=31 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/268845/New_Year_Honours_2014_notes_on_higher_awards.pdf |title=The New Year Honours List 2014 \u2013 Higher Awards |date=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n* Sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] on 19 July 2017.<ref name=\"privycouncil.independent.gov.uk\">{{cite web |url=https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/2017-07-19-List-of-Business-Part-1.pdf |title=Business Transacted and Orders Approved at The Privy Council Held by The Queen at Buckingham Palace on 19th July 2017 |access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n* Elected [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Fellow]] of [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/people/keir-starmer |title=Keir Starmer - Honorary Fellow |website=St Edmund Hall |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honorary degrees==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! School !! Degree\n|-\n| 21 July 2011\n| [[University of Essex]]\n| [[Honorary degree|Doctor of University]] (D.U.)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essex.ac.uk/honorary_graduates/ |title=Honorary Graduates - Profile: Keir Starmer QC |publisher=University of Essex |date= |accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 16 July 2012\n| [[University of Leeds]]\n| [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/130509/honorary_graduates |title=Honorary graduates |first=Tanya |last=O'Rourke |website=www.leeds.ac.uk |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 19 November 2013\n| [[University of East London]]\n| [[Honorary degree|Doctor of University]] (D.U.)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newhamrecorder.co.uk/news/education/keir-starmer-qc-awarded-honorary-doctorate-by-east-london-university-1-3016174 |title=Keir Starmer QC, awarded honorary doctorate by east London university |first=Kay |last=Atwal |website=Newham Recorder |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 19 December 2013 \n| [[London School of Economics]]\n| [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/intranet/LSEServices/governanceAndCommittees/lse_honorary_degrees.aspx |title=LSE Honorary Degrees |first=Dan |last=Bennett |website=www.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lse.ac.uk/website-archive/newsAndMedia/newsArchives/2013/12/KeirStarmer.aspx |title=Keir Starmer QC awarded an LSE Honorary Degree |website=www.lse.ac.uk |accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 14 July 2014\n| [[University of Reading]]\n| [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reading.ac.uk/news-and-events/releases/PR589467.aspx |date=14 July 2014 |title=Leading legal figure awarded Honorary Degree |publisher=University of Reading |access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 18 November 2014\n| [[University of Worcester]]\n| [[Honorary degree|Doctor of University]] (D.U.)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.worcester.ac.uk/community/sir-keir-starmer-kcb-qc-graduation-2014.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116001126/https://www.worcester.ac.uk/community/sir-keir-starmer-kcb-qc-graduation-2014.html |archive-date=16 November 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Publications ==\nStarmer is the author and editor of several books about criminal law and human rights:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* ''Justice in error'', ed. by Clive Walker and Keir Starmer (London: Blackstone, 1993), {{ISBN|1-85431-234-0}}\n* Francesca Klug, Keir Starmer and Stuart Weir, ''The three pillars of liberty: political rights and freedoms in the United Kingdom'' (London: Routledge, 1996), {{ISBN|0-415-09641-3}}\n* Conor Foley and Keir Starmer, ''Signing up for human rights: the United Kingdom and international standards'' (London: Amnesty International United Kingdom, 1998), {{ISBN|1-873328-30-3}}\n* ''Miscarriages of justice: a review of justice in error'', ed. by Clive Walker and Keir Starmer (London: Blackstone, 1999), {{ISBN|1-85431-687-7}}\n* Keir Starmer, ''European human rights law: the Human Rights Act 1998 and the European Convention on Human Rights'' (London: Legal Action Group, 1999), {{ISBN|0-905099-77-X}}\n* Keir Starmer, Michelle Strange, and Quincy Whitaker, with Anthony Jennings and Tim Owen, ''Criminal justice, police powers and human rights'' (London: Blackstone, 2001), {{ISBN|1-84174-138-8}}\n* Keir Starmer with Iain Byrne, ''Blackstone's human rights digest'' (London: Blackstone, 2001), {{ISBN|1-84174-153-1}}\n* Keir Starmer and Jane Gordon, ''A report on the policing of the Ardoyne parades 12 July 2004'' (Belfast: Northern Ireland Policing Board, 2004)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|www.keirstarmer.com}}\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=keir-starmer/4514 |publicwhip=Keir_Starmer |theywork=keir_starmer}}\n*[http://www.cps.gov.uk/about/dpp.html CPS]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ken Macdonald]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Director of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)|Director of Public Prosecutions]]|years=2008\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alison Saunders]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Frank Dobson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Holborn and St Pancras (UK Parliament constituency)|Holborn and St Pancras]]|years=[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Emily Thornberry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=Office Abolished}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Corbyn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Corbyn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Leaders of the Opposition UK}}\n{{Shadow Great Officers of State}}\n{{Leaders of political parties in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2020}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starmer, Keir}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Reigate Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Directors of Public Prosecutions (England and Wales)]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Lawyers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Kentish Town]]\n[[Category:People from Reigate]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 2001\u2013]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Labour Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (United Kingdom)]]\n", "name_user": "Butwhatdoiknow", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:move clause", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keir_Starmer"}
{"title_page": "Dana Rosemary Scallon", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name           = Dana Rosemary Scallon\n| image          = Ierse zangeres Dana arriveert op Schiphol voor Eurovisie Song Festival . Dana, Bestanddeelnr 923-3512.jpg\n| alt            = Dana Scallon in 1970\n| caption        = Pictured on arrival at [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]] on 16 March 1970\n| image_size     = \n| landscape      = \n| alias          = Dana\n| background     = solo_singer\n| birth_name     = Rosemary Brown\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1951|8|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Islington]], [[London]], England, UK\n| genre          = [[Celtic music|Celtic]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Christian music|Christian]]\n| years_active   = 1967\u2013present\n| label          = [[Rex Records (1965)|Rex]], [[Decca Records|Decca]], [[GTO Records|GTO]], [[Creole Records|Creole]], [[Warwick Records (United Kingdom)|Warwick]], [[Fanfare Records|Fanfare]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], [[Heart Beat Records|Heart Beat]], [[Lite Records|Lite]], [[Ritz Records|Ritz]], [[Word Records|Word]], [[DS Music]], [[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]], [[FOD Records]]\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.danaofficial.com}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Dana Rosemary Scallon\n|image           = \n|parliament      = European\n|office          = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n|constituency    = [[Connacht\u2013Ulster (European Parliament constituency)|Connacht\u2013Ulster]]\n|term_start      = 11 June 1999\n|term_end        = 11 June 2004\n|predecessor     = [[Mark Killilea Jnr|Mark Killilea]]\n|successor       = Constituency abolished\n|birth_date      = \n|birth_place     = \n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|spouse          = Damien Scallon\n|children        = Four\n|party           = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n}}\n'''Dana Rosemary Scallon''' (born '''Rosemary Brown''' on 30 August 1951),<ref>[http://www.dailycatholic.org/issue/archives/1999Aug/152aug13,vol.10,no.152-157txt/aug13dc5.htm Dana Scallon:   A powerful political voice for Catholicism through song and commitment]. ''Daily Catholic''. 13-22 August 1999, vol 10, no. 152-157. Retrieved 2020-01-23.</ref> known professionally as '''Dana''', is an Irish singer and former politician who served as [[Member of the European Parliament]] from 1999 to 2004.\n\nWhile still a schoolgirl she won the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1970|1970 Eurovision Song Contest]] with \"[[All Kinds of Everything]]\". It became a worldwide million-seller and launched her music career.\n\nShe entered politics in 1997, as Dana Rosemary Scallon, running unsuccessfully in the [[1997 Irish presidential election|Irish presidential election]], but later being elected as an MEP for [[Connacht\u2013Ulster (European Parliament constituency)|Connacht\u2013Ulster]] in 1999. Scallon was again an independent candidate in the [[2011 Irish presidential election|Irish 2011 presidential election]], but was eliminated on the first count. In 2019, Dana announced she was back in the studio and was recording a brand new album, her first in many years. 'My Time' was released 1 November 2019.\n\n==Background==\nScallon was born in Frederica Street, [[Islington]], [[North London]], to Robert and Sheila Brown (n\u00e9e Sheerin).<ref>[http://fp.martinunderwood.f9.co.uk/Ladykillers martinunderwood.co.uk \u2013 Frederica Street as seen in ''The Ladykillers'', a classic Ealing comedy made while Scallon was still living at number 89 (central character Mrs Wilberforce lived at \"number 57\", a set built at the end of the street).] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719171730/http://fp.martinunderwood.f9.co.uk/Ladykillers |date=19 July 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multimap.com/maps/#map=51.52823,0.11635%7c19%7C256&be=12453910%7cNorth&loc=GB:51.52823:-0.11635:17%7cfrederick%20street%20,%20london%7cFrederick%20Street,%20South%20Norwood,%20London,%20England,%20WC1X%209 |title=Frederica / Frederick Street now |website=Multimap.com |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> Her father worked as a porter at nearby [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross station]]. A hairdresser by trade, he'd relocated his family from his native [[Derry]] in [[Northern Ireland]] because of the high unemployment there after the [[World War II|war]]. She was five when her parents were advised by their doctor to return to Derry because of the [[Great Smog|London smog]], and the harmful effect it had on some of their children. (London had not yet benefited from the [[Clean Air Act 1956]].) Their new home was on Derry's [[Creggan, Derry|Creggan housing estate]] where they stayed until 1967, when they moved to the newly built Rossville Flats complex<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multimap.com/maps/?qs=rossville+street+northern+ireland&countryCode=GB#map=54.99681,-7.32551%7c19%7c256&be=24327342%7cNorth&bd=useful_information&loc=GB:54.99681:-7.32551:17%7crossville%20street%20northern%20ireland%7cRossville%20Street%20(B527),%20Londonderry,%20County%20Londonderry,%20Northern%20Ireland,%20BT48%209 |title=\u2013 Rossville Street today, where the flats once stood opposite Glenfada Park |website=Multimap.com |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> in the [[Bogside]], an area overlooked by the historic city walls.\n\nHer parents were musical \u2013 her father played the trumpet in his own dance band, The Imperial All Stars, and her mother was their guest pianist. They had seven children in all: three sons and four daughters, including their third-born child Grace who died at eight months\nfrom a [[Anaphylaxis|penicillin allergy]]. Fifth-born and youngest daughter Rosemary won the first talent contest she entered - an all-aged event at St Columb's Hall when she was six. During her childhood she was taught to play the piano and violin, taught herself to play the acoustic guitar, sang in the school choir, and at one point, after years of ballet practice, considered becoming a ballet teacher. She took part in many more music and dance contests. In 1965, the now solo Rosemary Brown took part in a local talent contest at the Embassy Ballroom, where she won first prize \u2013 a chance to record a [[Demo (music)|demo tape]]. Tony Johnston, a headmaster and part-time promoter who sponsored the competition, took her under his wing while she continued with her studies at [[Thornhill College]], the Roman Catholic grammar school for girls she joined in 1963.\n\nAfter gaining seven good grades in her [[General Certificate of Education|GCE O-level]] exams, [[Rex Records (1965)|Rex Records]] (Decca) in Dublin received her demo and manager Michael Geoghegan signed her up. Her debut single was \"Sixteen\", written by Tony Johnston, while the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]], \"Little Girl Blue\", was her own composition. It came out on 17 November 1967, but failed to take off, though local TV and radio began to show an interest in her. It was at this time that she adopted the professional name of \"Dana\", which had been her school nickname. Now studying [[A-level]] music and English, she became popular in Dublin's cabaret and folk clubs at weekends, and was crowned Queen of Cabaret at [[Clontarf Castle]] in 1968. Rex Records' secretary Phil Mitton suggested she audition for the Irish National Song Contest, due to take place in February 1969 \u2013 a victory would see her represent Ireland in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. With mixed feelings due to nerves she made it through to the final in Dublin where she sang \"Look Around\" by Michael Reade, later released as her fourth single. Shown live on Irish television, Scallon came second to [[Muriel Day]] and \"Wages of Love\", also written by Reade.\n\n==1970s \u2013 Eurovision victory and pop career==\nIn December 1969 Tom McGrath, producer of the Irish National Song Contest, invited Scallon to try again next year, feeling that one of the entered songs, the ballad \"All Kinds of Everything\", would suit her. Her second attempt to win the Irish contest was a success. Then on Saturday 21 March 1970, the eighteen-year-old schoolgirl performed the song at the Eurovision finals held in the [[Amsterdam RAI Exhibition and Convention Centre]], before an estimated viewing audience of two hundred million. Perched on a stool while wearing an embroidered white mini-dress, she was the last of twelve contestants to perform that night. After the voting had finished she was declared the winner with 32 points, beating the favourite, UK's [[Mary Hopkin]], with 26 and Germany's [[Katja Ebstein]] with 12. Spain's [[Julio Iglesias]] came equal fourth with [[Guy Bonnet]] of France and [[Henri D\u00e8s]] of Switzerland. This was [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Ireland's first of a record seven successes in the contest]].\n\nThe winning song was composed by two Dublin [[compositor (typesetting)|printworkers]], Derry Lindsay and Jackie Smith. The single was produced by Ray Horricks and arranged by [[Phil Coulter]]. Released on 14 March, it shot to #1 in the [[Irish singles chart]] before the contest began and stayed there for nine weeks. It also spent two weeks at the top of the [[UK singles chart]] on [[List of UK Singles Chart number ones of the 1970s|18 and 25 April]]. It was also successful in Australia, Austria, Germany, Israel, Malaysia, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Singapore, South Africa, Switzerland and Yugoslavia. The song went on to sell more than two million units.\n\nScallon's debut album ''All Kinds of Everything'', recorded at [[Decca Studios]] in West Hampstead, London, on the weekend of 25 April 1970, was released in June and included four tracks co-written by the singer, as well as a new recording of the album's title track. Her follow-up single was issued in September, but [[Jerry Lordan]]'s \"I Will Follow You\" failed to chart. The song that put an end to her [[one-hit wonder]] status was found on the album ''Barry Ryan 3''. \"Who Put the Lights Out\", written by [[Paul Ryan (singer)|Paul Ryan]] for his twin brother, was offered to her by their stepfather [[Marion Ryan|Harold Davison]], the business partner of her agent Dick Katz. Her version, cut with [[Barry Ryan (singer)|Barry Ryan]]'s producer Bill Landis, proved a strong comeback vehicle reaching #5 in Ireland. In the UK it became a #14 hit on 13 March 1971. There then followed three years of unsuccessful singles broken only by the Irish chart showing of \"Sunday Monday Tuesday\", a #4 hit in December 1973. This lack of success caused her agent to recommend she join the former head of [[Bell Records]] Dick Leahy on his new label, [[GTO Records]].\n\nShe debuted on GTO with \"Please Tell Him That I Said Hello\", written by Mike Shepstone and Peter Dibbens. Within a month of its release in October 1974 it was #7 in Ireland. It took until the new year before making its UK chart debut in January. Boosted by ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' performances on 6 February and 13 March, it climbed to #8 on 15 March 1975. This UK success gave the track a resurgence of popularity in Ireland where it rose to #7 again, this time in February. She also recorded a German version of the song. \"Spiel nicht mit mir und meinem Gl\u00fcck\" was a #27 hit in that country the same year. Scallon made a number of foreign singles, such as \"Wenn ein M\u00e4dchen verliebt ist\" (German, 1971), \"Tu Me Dis I Love You\" (French, 1975), and a Japanese version of \"It's Gonna be a Cold Cold Christmas\" in 1976.\n\nHer next single, \"Are You Still Mad at Me\", a [[Geoff Stephens]]/[[Roger Greenaway]] composition, missed the chart. They then wrote another song for her. \"It's Gonna be a Cold Cold Christmas\" was released four weeks prior to Christmas and gave her her second-highest UK chart position when it reached #4 on 27 December 1975. In Ireland it made #3, and the following year #12. At the end of the year Scallon collected two awards \u2013 Best Female Singer in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] from the ''[[NME]]'', and Best Female Singer from the ''[[TV Times]]''. The success continued into 1976, with a cover of [[Eric Carmen]]'s \"Never Gonna Fall in Love Again\" becoming a UK #31 hit on 13 March. In September however, while promoting her new single, \"Fairytale\", she lost her voice. Her left vocal cord, which had been [[cauterize]]d the year before, required urgent surgery to remove what turned out to be a non-malignant growth, as well as a small part of the cord itself. This caused some newspapers to report on the possibility that she might never sing again. Despite her inability to fully promote \"Fairytale\", a disco number written by Paul Greedus and produced by [[Barry Blue]], it became a UK #13 hit on Christmas Day, and was also her biggest international success since \"All Kinds of Everything\". But having failed to regain her singing voice after the operation, she contacted Florence Wiese Norberg, a respected singing teacher. With her help she resumed live performances with a week-long engagement at Caesar's Palace in Luton in December 1977.\n\nBarry Blue started work on her fifth album soon after finishing work on [[Heatwave (band)|Heatwave]]'s [[Central Heating (Heatwave album)|second album]], released in April 1978. Her final session at Utopia Studios in London ended two weeks before her wedding day in October. Issued in April 1979, ''The Girl is Back'' was the first LP she made that contained no [[cover versions]], and the track that rocked the most, \"Something's Cookin' in the Kitchen\" by Dave Jordan, became its only UK hit single, reaching #44 on 14 April. A disappointing result after a marketing campaign that included a new look for Scallon, a music video, life-size posters in major cities, and retailers receiving bonus [[flexi disc]]s. In Ireland it made #22. The album's title track was also released, followed by \"I Can't Get Over Getting Over You\", which she sang live on ''Top of the Pops'' in October, her final appearance on the show. The sad and reflective track \"Thieves of Paris\", written by Barry Blue and [[Lynsey de Paul]], has been rated one of the stand out tracks on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://macaenese5354.blogspot.com/2011_01_01_archive.html |title=\u9676\u9189\u7684\u516d\u4e03\u5341\u5e74\u4ee3\u60c5\u61f7: January 2011 |website=Macaenese5354.blogspot.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-22}}</ref> They also wrote her 1972 single, \"Crossword Puzzle\", a #2 hit in Thailand.\n\nA new phase in her career began after [[Pope John Paul II]] came to Ireland in September 1979, inspiring her to write with her husband the Irish chart-topper, \"Totus Tuus\".\n\nOutside her chart career, Scallon had remained a popular personality since her 1970 Eurovision win. She had played the part of a [[Irish traveller|tinker]] girl in ''[[Flight of the Doves]]'' (1971), a children's adventure film starring [[Ron Moody]] and [[Jack Wild]] and directed by [[Ralph Nelson]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0067104/ imdb.com \u2013 ''Flight of the Doves'']</ref> She also performed in summer seasons at resorts and seasonal pantomimes as well as performing at venues such as the [[Royal Albert Hall]], the [[Royal Festival Hall]] and a week of sell-out shows at the [[London Palladium]]. Scallon also performed extensively in cabaret venues and was voted Top Female Vocalist at the National Club Acts Awards in 1979. [[BBC Television]] gave her two shows of her own: a series of ''[[A Day with Dana]]'' in 1974 and four series of ''Wake Up Sunday'' in 1979. For [[BBC Radio]] she presented a series of ''I Believe in Music'' in 1977.\n\n==1980s \u2013 Catholic music==\nHaving scored an Irish number one in January 1980 with the song that was based on the Pope's motto: [[Totus Tuus]], Latin for Totally Yours, the much larger American Christian market became a possible outlet for her music. Not long after returning home from a promotional visit to the [[National Religious Broadcasters]] conference in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], opened by [[Jimmy Carter|US President Jimmy Carter]], she was contacted by award-winning songwriter [[Kurt Kaiser]], vice president of [[Word Records]]. He invited her back to the USA where she was offered a recording contract. Meanwhile, [[Warwick Records (United Kingdom)|Warwick Records]] issued ''Everything is Beautiful'' in late 1980. Recorded in September at Pye Studios in London, the LP subtitled ''20 Inspirational Songs'' was advertised on TV and became her biggest-selling album in the UK, reaching #43 in the chart on 10 January 1981. It was followed later that year by ''Totally Yours'', her first Christian album for Word Records; the songs \"Praise the Lord\", \"The Soft Rain\" and \"Totus Tuus\" were credited to \"Dana and Damien Scallon\". As was \"Little Baby (Grace's Song)\", written while she was pregnant with their first child.\n\nShe was soon back in the studios again to make ''Magic'' in 1982, a pop album for Lite Records made at [[Morgan Studios]] and Maison Rouge Studios in London. It included four songs by her younger brothers John and Gerald Brown, as well as the single \"I Feel Love Comin' On\", written by [[Barry White]], which peaked at #66 in the UK on 22 May. Collaborating with her younger brothers they wrote the official Northern Ireland [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] song \"Yer Man\", and she recorded it with the full [[1982 FIFA World Cup squads|squad]] before they headed to Spain for the finals. Following this, her second album for Word was completed; ''Let There Be Love'' contained up-tempo Christian pop, jazz, ballads, and an old Irish hymn sung in Gaelic called [[Ag Criost an Siol]].\n\nScallon starred in a [[London's West End|West End]] production of ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'', staged at the [[Phoenix Theatre (London)|Phoenix Theatre]] during the 1983 Christmas and New Year pantomime season. The venues first panto broke box-office records and was extended into February. She played ''Snow White'' for over fourteen years, each time in a different city, beginning the run at the [[Hull New Theatre|New Theatre]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] in 1982.\n\nA tour of America took place in 1984 to promote her two Word albums. Appearances were made in concert halls, churches, colleges and also on TV and radio.\n\nAfter fifteen years in show business [[Hodder and Stoughton]] published ''Dana \u2013 An Autobiography'' in 1985. It told the story of her childhood, married life and music career, as well as her growing devotion to God. At the same time as her book launch came the release of her fifties tribute album ''If I Give My Heart to You'', featuring her last UK chart entry \"Little Things Mean a Lot\", #92 on 13 July 1985. In Ireland in made #27, as did the album's title track.\n\nDue to work commitments in 1979, she wasn't in the country when Pope John Paul II became [[Pope John Paul II's visit to Ireland|the first pope ever to visit Ireland]]. But she eventually saw him in 1987 at the Superdome in [[New Orleans]], having been invited there to perform \"Totus Tuus\" before a gathering of 80,000 or more. After her performance the [[pontiff]] made his way to the stage to personally thank her for writing the song.\n\n==1990s \u2013 Politics==\nSoon after completing a concert tour of England in early 1990, she took her family to [[Florida]] for an [[Easter]] holiday. Her break was interrupted by a request to fly to [[Irondale, Alabama]] and make a guest appearance at [[Eternal Word Television Network]]'s (EWTN) tenth anniversary show. Afterwards, the network's founder [[Mother Angelica]] enquired if her ex-hotelier husband would like to work there, setting up a retreat centre to look after the hundreds of visitors the network attracted each day. Then mid holiday she sang at a Rosary Rally in [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]], and was asked to write a theme song for the [[Rosary]]. The result was ''The Rosary'', an album released with [[Heart Beat Records]] in 1991 that has amassed over a million sales around the world.\n\nBy August 1991 the Scallons were living in [[Mountain Brook, Alabama|Mountain Brook]], close to EWTN's headquarters where Damien now worked. Thoughts of winding down her career were dashed when her husband was asked if his wife would like to work there, presenting a music programme. ''Say Yes'' became the first TV series she made for them. Three more followed: ''We Are One Body'', ''Backstage'' and ''Dana and friends''. With this exposure she became a popular Catholic music singer, appearing at conferences and public gatherings across America. [[Heart Beat Records]], the US Catholic music label, issued a number of her music and prayer albums.\n\nTo help celebrate the sixth [[World Youth Day]] event held in [[Cherry Creek State Park]], Denver in 1993, she was invited to sing in the presence of Pope John Paul II the theme song for the occasion, \"We Are One Body\", a song she composed herself. She also sang at the World Youth Day celebrations held in [[Paris]] in 1997, Toronto in 2002 and Sydney in 2008.\n\nIn June 1997, she received a letter from the Christian Community Centre in Ireland suggesting she run for the [[President of Ireland|Irish presidency]]. Having no interest in politics at the time, and never having heard of that organisation, she threw the \"incredible\" proposal in the bin. But they persisted and similar mail arrived from other people. Then the media got involved. She eventually agreed to seek nomination as a candidate in the [[1997 Irish presidential election]], standing as an [[Independent (politician)|independent]] under the name Dana Rosemary Scallon. Her campaign was based on the [[Constitution of Ireland|Irish Constitution]] and her belief that it could only be amended with the agreement of the Irish people by public ballot. She later became the first-ever presidential candidate to secure a nomination solely from County and City Councils, rather than from members of the [[Oireachtas]]. Polling day was 31 October, and Scallon received 175,458 of the first-preference votes (13.8%), coming third to [[Fianna F\u00e1il]]'s candidate and eventual winner [[Mary McAleese]]. Before returning to America she told reporters: \"I may not be a president, but I ''am'' a [[precedent]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.herald.ie/opinion/terry-prone-with-mary-on-for-the-aras-the-contest-really-hots-up-2658423.html |title=With Mary on for the Aras the contest really hots up |work=[[Evening Herald]] |author=Terry Prone |date=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe was granted US citizenship in 1999, requiring her to swear an [[Oath of Allegiance (United States)|oath]] renouncing allegiance to any other state.<ref name=\"Dana denies US passport deception\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1007/president.html |title=Dana denies US passport deception |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheehan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/this-is-a-bid-to-discredit-me-i-wont-be-broken-2907429.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130218015034/http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/this-is-a-bid-to-discredit-me-i-wont-be-broken-2907429.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 February 2013 |title=This is a bid to discredit me -- I won't be broken |work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)]] |author=Maeve Sheehan |date=16 October 2011 }}</ref> That same year she again stood as an independent, this time winning a seat in the [[European Parliament]], representing Connacht\u2013Ulster. She campaigned on [[family values]] and her strong pro-life beliefs. Scallon is opposed to abortion in all cases, In 2013 she said \"there is no legal or constitutional obligation for politicians to legislate for the deliberate killing of an unborn child and there is no medical evidence to support this radical change to how we treat our mothers and their children and the taking of an innocent and defenceless human life can never be justified\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/dana-calls-for-referendum-on-abortion-law-1.1456045|title=Dana calls for referendum on abortion law|website=irishtimes.com|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> She was also vocal for her opposition to [[divorce]] and same sex marriage, along with a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] line on the [[European Union|EU]]. Scallon refused to associate with any political party despite Fianna F\u00e1il making several approaches for her to join them.<ref name=\"rte.ie\">As revealed in an interview, Conversations with Eamon Dunphy, 3 November 2007, RT\u00c9 Radio 1 {{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/eamondunphy/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420233110/http://www.rte.ie/radio1/eamondunphy/ |archivedate=20 April 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> On becoming an [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] her eight-year stay in the US came to an end.\n\n==2000s to present==\nIn 2001 she opposed a proposed amendment to the Irish constitution that would have legalised the \"[[Emergency contraception|morning after pill]]\" and [[Intrauterine device|IUD]]. The amendment was defeated in a referendum in 2002, although it was supported by the mainstream political parties. Scallon also had public disagreements at the time with the Catholic hierarchy (notably with Cardinal [[Desmond Connell]]), the latter wishing instead to negotiate a consensus solution.<ref name=\"rte.ie\"/>\n\nAs an independent she unsuccessfully contested a seat in [[Galway West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Galway West]] in the 2002 Irish general election, scoring just 3.5% of the first preference vote. In June 2004, Scallon lost her European Parliament seat, taking 13.5% of the vote. Later that year she failed to secure a nomination to the office of President of Ireland against the uncontested incumbent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=4459 |title=Dana election results at Elections Ireland |website=Electionsireland.org |date= |accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nReturning to the world of entertainment in 2005, she spent seven weeks on the RT\u00c9 television series ''The Afternoon Show'', where she did a fitness routine with a trainer and lost fifteen pounds in weight in time for her eldest daughter's wedding. In 2006, she and dancer Ronan McCormack were paired together in the RT\u00c9 dance series ''[[Celebrity Jigs 'n' Reels]]''. They made it to the final show and came second. That same year, Scallon and her husband launched their own music label, DS Music Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dana-music.com |title=DS Music Productions |website=Dana-music.com |accessdate=28 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926204058/http://www.dana-music.com/ |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> One of the first albums released was ''Totus Tuus'', a compilation of songs dedicated to the memory of Pope John Paul II and issued on the anniversary of his death. A children's album was released in 2007, along with a DVD in 2008, entitled ''Good Morning Jesus: Prayers & Songs for Children of All Ages'', which featured in a special series on EWTN. The Scallons and their new label were sued in 2007 by Heart Beat Records for copyright violations on several of the albums they'd recently released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dockets.justia.com/docket/court-iasdce/case_no-3:2007cv00066/case_id-34121/ |title=Heartbeat Records Inc v DS Music Production |website=Dockets.justia.com |date=20 July 2007 |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Gill & Macmillan]] published her second autobiography in 2007. Her political career took centre stage in ''All Kinds of Everything''. To coincide with the book launch, her first secular album since ''Forever Christmas'' a decade earlier, was released. ''A Thing Called Love'' was produced by her and her youngest brother Gerry, who also played guitar and keyboards, while her youngest son Robert played drums.\n\nIn 2009, Scallon became a judge on ''[[The All Ireland Talent Show]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterford-news.ie/news/story.asp?j=27044&cat=entertainment |title=Waterford News & Star: |website=Waterford-news.ie |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in the summer of 2010 she participated in the Best of British Variety tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehaven-news.co.uk/home/dana-set-to-star-in-town-1.747397?referrerPath=features/the-arts |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505145337/http://www.whitehaven-news.co.uk/home/dana-set-to-star-in-town-1.747397?referrerPath=features/the-arts |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |title=Home &#124; Dana set to star in town |publisher=Whitehaven News |date=18 August 2010 |accessdate=7 March 2011 }}</ref> She was a contestant in the fourth series of the reality television programme, ''[[Celebrity Bainisteoir]]'', in 2011, but was forced to withdraw by RT\u00c9 when she announced she would run for the Irish presidency again.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/0715/celebritybainisteoir.html \"RT\u00c9's Celebrity Bainisteoirs announced\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817232359/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/0715/celebritybainisteoir.html |date=17 August 2011 }}. ''RT\u00c9 Ten''. 15 July 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.midulstermail.co.uk/sport/lissan_gac_1_3071674 \"Lissan GAC\"]. ''Mid Ulster Mail''. 27 September 2011.</ref>\n\n===2011 presidential campaign===\n{{Main|2011 Irish presidential election}}\nOn 19 September 2011, at the Fitzwilliam Hotel on [[St Stephen's Green]], Scallon announced she would be seeking a nomination to enter the following month's Irish presidential election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/dana-seeks-help-from-all-sides-in-bid-to-nail-down-her-nomination-2881200.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120909020517/http://www.independent.ie/national-news/dana-seeks-help-from-all-sides-in-bid-to-nail-down-her-nomination-2881200.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 September 2012 |title=Dana seeks help from all sides in bid to nail down her nomination |publisher=Irish Independent |date=20 September 2011 |accessdate=20 September 2011 }}</ref> Carlow County Council was the first to nominate her.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newstalk.ie/2011/news/dana-get-first-aras-nomination-as-meetings-continue/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908102140/http://www.newstalk.ie/2011/news/dana-get-first-aras-nomination-as-meetings-continue/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 September 2012 |title=Dana get first Aras nomination, as meetings continue |publisher=Newstalk |date= |accessdate=26 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/carlow-votes-for-dana-522073.html |title=Carlow votes for Dana |publisher=Irish Examiner |date= |accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> She was then nominated by other county councils thus becoming a candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/dana-is-officially-a-presidential-candidate-following-offaly-nomination-238169-Sep2011/ |title=Dana is officially a presidential candidate following Offaly nomination |website=TheJournal.ie |date= |accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15078509 |title=Dana in Irish presidential election after fourth council nomination |website=Bbc.co.uk |date= 27 September 2011|accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref> There were seven candidates in total, five men and two women.\n\nIn the first debate, held on [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]]'s ''[[RT\u00c9 News at One|News at One]]'', independent candidate Scallon explained she had delayed her entry into the race due to numerous family bereavements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/0928/breaking4.html |title=\u00c1ras candidates set out positions in first debate |publisher=The Irish Times |date= |accessdate=28 September 2011 |first=Charlie |last=Taylor}}</ref> Appearing on ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' alongside the other candidates, Scallon displayed a copy of the EU Constitution, telling her audience: \"This is what this election is about. I have the knowledge and experience to be able to protect our sovereignty and that's the only question I think that's really urgent at this time.\" When asked by [[Ryan Tubridy]] if she would refuse to sign any bill threatening {{lang|ga|[[Constitution of Ireland|Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann]]}}, she responded by saying, \"You bet your boots I would\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2011/1001/1224305088913.html |title=Campaigns to cost up to \u20ac350,000, say candidates |work=The Irish Times |date= 1 October 2011|accessdate=1 October 2011 |first1=Marie |last1=O'Halloran |first2=Paul |last2=Cullen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/1001/breaking3.html?via=mr |title=\u00c1ras candidates dodge bullets |work=The Irish Times |date= |accessdate=1 October 2011 |first=Paul |last=Cullen}}</ref> In fact, the President does not have such a veto power, being able only to refer a Bill to the Council of State for its consideration.<ref>[http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/upload/static/256.htm Article 26, Constitution of Ireland] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516102833/http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/upload/static/256.htm |date=16 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSpeaking on [[Newstalk]]'s ''[[The Right Hook]]'' programme on 5 October 2011, Scallon said: \"I am not anti Europe. I have always said that Europe, the concept of Europe is good. We want to be in Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/dana-insists-i-am-not-anti-europe-246353-Oct2011/ |title=Dana insists: \u2018I am not anti-Europe\u2019 |publisher=The Journal |date= |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed on 7 October 2011 that Scallon had dual US and Irish citizenship, but she denied hiding this from the public, saying that her US citizenship, which involved her taking an [[oath of Allegiance (United States)|oath]] renouncing allegiance to Ireland, was not an issue then or now and she had no reason to hide it.<ref name=\"Dana denies US passport deception\"/>\n\nDuring a debate on ''[[Prime Time (Irish TV programme)|Prime Time]]'' ([[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]) on 12 October, Scallon read out a prepared statement towards the end of the debate, announcing that a \"malicious\" and \"false\" accusation had been made against her and her family in the United States and, while refusing to divulge any details, she said she would leave \"no stone unturned\" in her mission to track down the person or organisation responsible.<ref name=RTE_Debate_Live_12_Oct>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1012/president_tracker.html|title=Live - Prime Time Debate: 2247|work=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=12 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/ojcweykfcwql/|title=Dana criticises \"vile and false\" accusation against member of her family|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=12 October 2011}}</ref> The incident was described as \"bizarre\" by some media.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://breakingnews.ie/ireland/dana-future-in-presidential-campaign-in-doubt-524131.html|title=Dana future in presidential campaign in doubt|work=Breakingnews.ie|date=12 October 2011}}</ref> It later transpired that the statement referred to her brother, John Brown, who had been accused in 2008, in the course of litigation in the US among family members, of having sexually abused his niece. He denied the allegation.<ref name=\"Sheehan\"/> Brown was arrested by London police in June 2012, following a complaint against him made in October 2011. In May 2013, he was charged with three counts of indecent assault on two girls aged under 16.<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/danas-brother-charged-with-child-molestation-in-uk-29289710.html \"Dana's brother charged with child molestation in UK\"], Independent.ie, 23 May 2013</ref> John Brown was found not guilty and unanimously cleared on all charges on 25 July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-28482986 |title=John Brown, brother of Dana, cleared of 1970s sex abuse charges |website=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> Marian Finnucan of RT\u00c9 said he was falsely accused<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/marian-finucane/programmes/2014/0726/633234-marian-finucane-saturday-26-july-2014/?clipid=1638042 |title=Marian Finucane Saturday 26 July 2014 - Marian Finucane - RT\u00c9 Radio 1 |website=Rte.ie |date= |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> John Brown has since taken legal action against his accusers and a journalist and newspaper.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nVoting took place on 27 October and the fourth and final count was completed two days later. Scallon received 51,220 votes (2.9%) and came sixth to [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour's]] [[Michael D. Higgins]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15488067 |title=Irish presidential election: Michael D Higgins elected |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date= 29 October 2011 |accessdate=29 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===2019 new album===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=January 2020}}\nIn 2019, Dana announced she was back in the studio and was recording a brand new album, her first in many years. Scallon appeared on [[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]], [[RTE Today]] and various radio stations to promote new single 'Falling'. The album 'My Time' was released on 1 November 2019.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 5 October 1978 she married hotelier Damien Scallon at [[St Eugene's Cathedral]] in Derry, where her parents were married. The couple first met in 1970 at his Ardmore Hotel in Newry, where a reception took place following a \"Dana Place\" street-naming ceremony in nearby Hilltown, to honour her recent Eurovision success. After a three-week honeymoon in [[Grenada]] {{citation needed|date=September 2018}} the newlyweds set up home in [[Rostrevor]], County Down.{{cn|date=January 2020}} They have four children: Grace (born 1981), Ruth (born 1983), John James (born 1984), and Robert (born 1989).{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe Scallons currently live in [[Claregalway]], [[County Galway]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.galwaynews.ie/21624-claregalway-resident-dana-intends-run-president |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120801131111/http://www.galwaynews.ie/21624-claregalway-resident-dana-intends-run-president |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 August 2012 |title=Claregalway Resident Dana Intends To Run For President |website=Galwaynews.ie |date=22 September 2011 |accessdate=28 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!'''Singles'''!!'''Albums'''<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 139}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"width:50%;\"|\n\n*1967 \"Sixteen\"\n*1968 \"Come Along Murphy\"\n*1968 \"Heidschi Bumbeidschi\"\n*1969 \"Look Around\"\n*1970 \"[[All Kinds of Everything]]\" (Ireland #1, UK #1, Austria #7, Germany #4, Netherlands #2, New Zealand #19, South Africa #7, Switzerland #7)\n*1970 \"I Will Follow You\"\n*1971 \"Who Put the Lights Out\" (Ireland #5, UK #14)\n*1971 \"Today\"\n*1971 \"[[Isn't It a Pity]]\"\n*1972 \"New Days...New Ways\"\n*1972 \"Crossword Puzzle\" (Thailand #2)\n*1973 \"Do I Still Figure in Your Life\"\n*1973 \"Sunday Monday Tuesday\" (Ireland #4)\n*1974 \"Please Tell Him That I Said Hello\" (Germany #27<sup>1</sup>, Ireland #7, UK #8<br/><sup>1</sup>as \"Spiel nicht mit mir und meinem Gl\u00fcck\")\n*1975 \"Are You Still Mad at Me\"\n*1975 \"It's Gonna Be a Cold Cold Christmas\" (Ireland #3 [1976 reissue #12], UK #4)\n*1976 \"[[Never Gonna Fall in Love Again]]\" (UK #31)\n*1976 \"Rivers Are for Boats\"\n*1976 \"Fairytale\" (Mexico #1, Germany #21, Austria #19, Belgium/Flemish Region #4, Netherlands #3, UK #13)\n*1976 \"[[I Love How You Love Me]]\" (Netherlands #27)\n*1977 \"Put Some Words Together\"\n*1979 \"Something's Cookin' in the Kitchen\" (UK #44, Ireland #22)\n*1979  \"The Girl is Back\"\n*1979 \"I Can't Get Over Getting Over You\"\n*1979 \"Totus Tuus\" (Ireland #1)\n*1980 \"[[When a Child is Born]]\"\n*1981 \"[[Lady of Knock]]\" (Ireland #23)\n*1981 \"[[Dream Lover]]\" (Ireland #26)\n*1982 \"[[Felice Taylor|I Feel Love Comin' On]]\" (UK #66)\n*1982 \"Yer Man\"\n*1982 \"You Never Gave Me Your Love\" / \"Marathon\"\n*1982 \"If You Really Love Me\"\n*1985 \"[[Little Things Mean a Lot]]\" (UK #92, Ireland #27)\n*1985 \"[[If I Give My Heart to You]]\" (Ireland #27)\n*1986 \"[[Everything Is Beautiful]]\" (Ireland #42)\n*1987 \"[[Lipstick on Your Collar (song)|Lipstick on Your Collar]]\"\n*1988 \"Summer Romeo\"\n*1989 \"Harmony\"\n*2005 \"Children of the World\"\n*2019 ''Falling''\n|\n*1970 ''All Kinds of Everything''\n*1975 ''The World of Dana''\n*1975 ''Have a Nice Day''\n*1976 ''Love Songs & Fairytales''\n*1979 ''The Girl is Back''\n*1980 ''Everything is Beautiful'' (UK #43)\n*1981 ''Totally Yours''\n*1982 ''Magic''\n*1983 ''Let There Be Love''\n*1984 ''Please Tell Him That I Said Hello''\n*1985 ''If I Give My Heart to You''\n*1987 ''In the Palm Of His Hand''\n*1987 ''No Greater Love''\n*1989 ''The Gift of Love''\n*1990 ''All Kinds of Everything'' (compilation)\n*1991 ''Dana's Ireland''\n*1991 ''The Rosary''\n*1992 ''Lady of Knock''\n*1993 ''Hail Holy Queen''\n*1993 ''Say Yes!''\n*1995 ''The Healing Rosary''\n*1996 ''Dana The Collection''\n*1997 ''Humble Myself''\n*1997 ''Forever Christmas''\n*1997 ''Heavenly Portrait''\n*1998 ''The Best of Dana''\n*1998 ''Stations of The Cross''\n*2004 ''Perfect Gift''\n*2005 ''In Memory of Me''\n*2006 ''Totus Tuus''\n*2007 ''Good Morning Jesus!''\n*2007 ''A Thing Called Love''\n*2012 ''Praise & Thanks''\n*2012 ''Ave Maria''\n*2019 ''My Time''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dana Scallon}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180805080642/http://danaofficial.com/ Official website of Dana]\n* {{IMDb name|0199043}}\n\n* [https://www.facebook.com/DanaofficialFOD Facebook: Official Dana Facebook]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCBpIpEqO4PNzrU52je54OOA YouTube channel: Official Dana YouTube]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/Iwillfollowyou YouTube channel: Friends of DANA]\n* {{MEP|4389|Dana Rosemary Scallon}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Muriel Day]]<br/>with \"[[The Wages of Love]]\"}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest]]|years=1970}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Angela Farrell]]<br/>with \"[[One Day Love]]\"}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before={{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] with \"[[Boom Bang-a-Bang]]\"<br/>{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Salom\u00e9 (singer)|Salom\u00e9]] with \"[[Vivo cantando]]\"<br/>{{flagicon|France}} [[Frida Boccara]]<br/>with \"[[Un jour, un enfant]]\"<br/>{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Lenny Kuhr]]<br/>with \"[[De troubadour]]\"<br/>(four-way tie)}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Eurovision Song Contest winners|Winner of the Eurovision Song Contest]]|years=[[Eurovision Song Contest 1970|1970]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{flagicon|Monaco}} [[S\u00e9verine (singer)|S\u00e9verine]]<br/>with \"[[Un banc, un arbre, une rue]]\"}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Killilea Jnr|Mark Killilea]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of the European Parliament]]<br/>for [[Connacht\u2013Ulster (European Parliament constituency)|Connacht\u2013Ulster]]|years=1999\u20132004}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{List of Eurovision Song Contest winners}}\n{{Members of the European Parliament for Ireland (1999\u20132004)}}\n{{Celebrity Bainisteoir}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scallon, Dana Rosemary}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Islington (district)]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest entrants of 1970]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest winners]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Independent Ireland MEPs]]\n[[Category:Independent politicians in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Irish anti-abortion activists]]\n[[Category:Irish Eurovision Song Contest entrants]]\n[[Category:Irish female singers]]\n[[Category:Irish pop musicians]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the Republic of Ireland 1999\u20132004]]\n[[Category:People educated at Thornhill College]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Northern Ireland descent]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Derry (city)]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name           = Dana Rosemary Scallon\n| image          = Ierse zangeres Dana arriveert op Schiphol voor Eurovisie Song Festival . Dana, Bestanddeelnr 923-3512.jpg\n| alt            = Dana Scallon in 1970\n| caption        = Pictured on arrival at [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]] on 16 March 1970\n| image_size     = \n| landscape      = \n| alias          = Dana\n| background     = solo_singer\n| birth_name     = Rosemary Brown\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1951|8|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Islington]], [[London]], England, UK\n| genre          = [[Celtic music|Celtic]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Christian music|Christian]]\n| years_active   = 1967\u2013present\n| label          = [[Rex Records (1965)|Rex]], [[Decca Records|Decca]], [[GTO Records|GTO]], [[Creole Records|Creole]], [[Warwick Records (United Kingdom)|Warwick]], [[Fanfare Records|Fanfare]], [[Epic Records|Epic]], [[Heart Beat Records|Heart Beat]], [[Lite Records|Lite]], [[Ritz Records|Ritz]], [[Word Records|Word]], [[DS Music]], [[Cherry Red Records|Cherry Red]], [[FOD Records]]\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.danaofficial.com}}\n}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Dana Rosemary Scallon\n|image           = \n|parliament      = European\n|office          = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n|constituency    = [[Connacht\u2013Ulster (European Parliament constituency)|Connacht\u2013Ulster]]\n|term_start      = 11 June 1999\n|term_end        = 11 June 2004\n|predecessor     = [[Mark Killilea Jnr|Mark Killilea]]\n|successor       = Constituency abolished\n|birth_date      = \n|birth_place     = \n|death_date      = \n|death_place     = \n|spouse          = Damien Scallon\n|children        = Four\n|party           = [[Independent (politician)|Independent]]\n}}\n'''Dana Rosemary Scallon''' (born '''Rosemary Brown''' on 30 August 1951),<ref>[http://www.dailycatholic.org/issue/archives/1999Aug/152aug13,vol.10,no.152-157txt/aug13dc5.htm Dana Scallon:   A powerful political voice for Catholicism through song and commitment]. ''Daily Catholic''. 13-22 August 1999, vol 10, no. 152-157. Retrieved 2020-01-23.</ref> known professionally as '''Dana''', is an Irish singer and former politician who served as [[Member of the European Parliament]] from 1999 to 2004.\n\nWhile still a schoolgirl she won the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1970|1970 Eurovision Song Contest]] with \"[[All Kinds of Everything]]\". It became a worldwide million-seller and launched her music career.\n\nShe entered politics in 1997, as Dana Rosemary Scallon, running unsuccessfully in the [[1997 Irish presidential election|Irish presidential election]], but later being elected as an MEP for [[Connacht\u2013Ulster (European Parliament constituency)|Connacht\u2013Ulster]] in 1999. Scallon was again an independent candidate in the [[2011 Irish presidential election|Irish 2011 presidential election]], but was eliminated on the first count. In 2019, Dana announced she was back in the studio and was recording a brand new album, her first in many years. 'My Time' was released 1st November 2019.\n\n==Background==\nScallon was born in Frederica Street, [[Islington]], [[North London]], to Robert and Sheila Brown (n\u00e9e Sheerin).<ref>[http://fp.martinunderwood.f9.co.uk/Ladykillers martinunderwood.co.uk \u2013 Frederica Street as seen in ''The Ladykillers'', a classic Ealing comedy made while Scallon was still living at number 89 (central character Mrs Wilberforce lived at \"number 57\", a set built at the end of the street).] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060719171730/http://fp.martinunderwood.f9.co.uk/Ladykillers |date=19 July 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multimap.com/maps/#map=51.52823,0.11635%7c19%7C256&be=12453910%7cNorth&loc=GB:51.52823:-0.11635:17%7cfrederick%20street%20,%20london%7cFrederick%20Street,%20South%20Norwood,%20London,%20England,%20WC1X%209 |title=Frederica / Frederick Street now |website=Multimap.com |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> Her father worked as a porter at nearby [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross station]]. A hairdresser by trade, he'd relocated his family from his native [[Derry]] in [[Northern Ireland]] because of the high unemployment there after the [[World War II|war]]. She was five when her parents were advised by their doctor to return to Derry because of the [[Great Smog|London smog]], and the harmful effect it had on some of their children. (London had not yet benefited from the [[Clean Air Act 1956]].) Their new home was on Derry's [[Creggan, Derry|Creggan housing estate]] where they stayed until 1967, when they moved to the newly built Rossville Flats complex<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.multimap.com/maps/?qs=rossville+street+northern+ireland&countryCode=GB#map=54.99681,-7.32551%7c19%7c256&be=24327342%7cNorth&bd=useful_information&loc=GB:54.99681:-7.32551:17%7crossville%20street%20northern%20ireland%7cRossville%20Street%20(B527),%20Londonderry,%20County%20Londonderry,%20Northern%20Ireland,%20BT48%209 |title=\u2013 Rossville Street today, where the flats once stood opposite Glenfada Park |website=Multimap.com |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> in the [[Bogside]], an area overlooked by the historic city walls.\n\nHer parents were musical \u2013 her father played the trumpet in his own dance band, The Imperial All Stars, and her mother was their guest pianist. They had seven children in all: three sons and four daughters, including their third-born child Grace who died at eight months\nfrom a [[Anaphylaxis|penicillin allergy]]. Fifth-born and youngest daughter Rosemary won the first talent contest she entered - an all-aged event at St Columb's Hall when she was six. During her childhood she was taught to play the piano and violin, taught herself to play the acoustic guitar, sang in the school choir, and at one point, after years of ballet practice, considered becoming a ballet teacher. She took part in many more music and dance contests. In 1965, the now solo Rosemary Brown took part in a local talent contest at the Embassy Ballroom, where she won first prize \u2013 a chance to record a [[Demo (music)|demo tape]]. Tony Johnston, a headmaster and part-time promoter who sponsored the competition, took her under his wing while she continued with her studies at [[Thornhill College]], the Roman Catholic grammar school for girls she joined in 1963.\n\nAfter gaining seven good grades in her [[General Certificate of Education|GCE O-level]] exams, [[Rex Records (1965)|Rex Records]] (Decca) in Dublin received her demo and manager Michael Geoghegan signed her up. Her debut single was \"Sixteen\", written by Tony Johnston, while the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]], \"Little Girl Blue\", was her own composition. It came out on 17 November 1967, but failed to take off, though local TV and radio began to show an interest in her. It was at this time that she adopted the professional name of \"Dana\", which had been her school nickname. Now studying [[A-level]] music and English, she became popular in Dublin's cabaret and folk clubs at weekends, and was crowned Queen of Cabaret at [[Clontarf Castle]] in 1968. Rex Records' secretary Phil Mitton suggested she audition for the Irish National Song Contest, due to take place in February 1969 \u2013 a victory would see her represent Ireland in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. With mixed feelings due to nerves she made it through to the final in Dublin where she sang \"Look Around\" by Michael Reade, later released as her fourth single. Shown live on Irish television, Scallon came second to [[Muriel Day]] and \"Wages of Love\", also written by Reade.\n\n==1970s \u2013 Eurovision victory and pop career==\nIn December 1969 Tom McGrath, producer of the Irish National Song Contest, invited Scallon to try again next year, feeling that one of the entered songs, the ballad \"All Kinds of Everything\", would suit her. Her second attempt to win the Irish contest was a success. Then on Saturday 21 March 1970, the eighteen-year-old schoolgirl performed the song at the Eurovision finals held in the [[Amsterdam RAI Exhibition and Convention Centre]], before an estimated viewing audience of two hundred million. Perched on a stool while wearing an embroidered white mini-dress, she was the last of twelve contestants to perform that night. After the voting had finished she was declared the winner with 32 points, beating the favourite, UK's [[Mary Hopkin]], with 26 and Germany's [[Katja Ebstein]] with 12. Spain's [[Julio Iglesias]] came equal fourth with [[Guy Bonnet]] of France and [[Henri D\u00e8s]] of Switzerland. This was [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Ireland's first of a record seven successes in the contest]].\n\nThe winning song was composed by two Dublin [[compositor (typesetting)|printworkers]], Derry Lindsay and Jackie Smith. The single was produced by Ray Horricks and arranged by [[Phil Coulter]]. Released on 14 March, it shot to #1 in the [[Irish singles chart]] before the contest began and stayed there for nine weeks. It also spent two weeks at the top of the [[UK singles chart]] on [[List of UK Singles Chart number ones of the 1970s|18 and 25 April]]. It was also successful in Australia, Austria, Germany, Israel, Malaysia, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Singapore, South Africa, Switzerland and Yugoslavia. The song went on to sell more than two million units.\n\nScallon's debut album ''All Kinds of Everything'', recorded at [[Decca Studios]] in West Hampstead, London, on the weekend of 25 April 1970, was released in June and included four tracks co-written by the singer, as well as a new recording of the album's title track. Her follow-up single was issued in September, but [[Jerry Lordan]]'s \"I Will Follow You\" failed to chart. The song that put an end to her [[one-hit wonder]] status was found on the album ''Barry Ryan 3''. \"Who Put the Lights Out\", written by [[Paul Ryan (singer)|Paul Ryan]] for his twin brother, was offered to her by their stepfather [[Marion Ryan|Harold Davison]], the business partner of her agent Dick Katz. Her version, cut with [[Barry Ryan (singer)|Barry Ryan]]'s producer Bill Landis, proved a strong comeback vehicle reaching #5 in Ireland. In the UK it became a #14 hit on 13 March 1971. There then followed three years of unsuccessful singles broken only by the Irish chart showing of \"Sunday Monday Tuesday\", a #4 hit in December 1973. This lack of success caused her agent to recommend she join the former head of [[Bell Records]] Dick Leahy on his new label, [[GTO Records]].\n\nShe debuted on GTO with \"Please Tell Him That I Said Hello\", written by Mike Shepstone and Peter Dibbens. Within a month of its release in October 1974 it was #7 in Ireland. It took until the new year before making its UK chart debut in January. Boosted by ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' performances on 6 February and 13 March, it climbed to #8 on 15 March 1975. This UK success gave the track a resurgence of popularity in Ireland where it rose to #7 again, this time in February. She also recorded a German version of the song. \"Spiel nicht mit mir und meinem Gl\u00fcck\" was a #27 hit in that country the same year. Scallon made a number of foreign singles, such as \"Wenn ein M\u00e4dchen verliebt ist\" (German, 1971), \"Tu Me Dis I Love You\" (French, 1975), and a Japanese version of \"It's Gonna be a Cold Cold Christmas\" in 1976.\n\nHer next single, \"Are You Still Mad at Me\", a [[Geoff Stephens]]/[[Roger Greenaway]] composition, missed the chart. They then wrote another song for her. \"It's Gonna be a Cold Cold Christmas\" was released four weeks prior to Christmas and gave her her second-highest UK chart position when it reached #4 on 27 December 1975. In Ireland it made #3, and the following year #12. At the end of the year Scallon collected two awards \u2013 Best Female Singer in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] from the ''[[NME]]'', and Best Female Singer from the ''[[TV Times]]''. The success continued into 1976, with a cover of [[Eric Carmen]]'s \"Never Gonna Fall in Love Again\" becoming a UK #31 hit on 13 March. In September however, while promoting her new single, \"Fairytale\", she lost her voice. Her left vocal cord, which had been [[cauterize]]d the year before, required urgent surgery to remove what turned out to be a non-malignant growth, as well as a small part of the cord itself. This caused some newspapers to report on the possibility that she might never sing again. Despite her inability to fully promote \"Fairytale\", a disco number written by Paul Greedus and produced by [[Barry Blue]], it became a UK #13 hit on Christmas Day, and was also her biggest international success since \"All Kinds of Everything\". But having failed to regain her singing voice after the operation, she contacted Florence Wiese Norberg, a respected singing teacher. With her help she resumed live performances with a week-long engagement at Caesar's Palace in Luton in December 1977.\n\nBarry Blue started work on her fifth album soon after finishing work on [[Heatwave (band)|Heatwave]]'s [[Central Heating (Heatwave album)|second album]], released in April 1978. Her final session at Utopia Studios in London ended two weeks before her wedding day in October. Issued in April 1979, ''The Girl is Back'' was the first LP she made that contained no [[cover versions]], and the track that rocked the most, \"Something's Cookin' in the Kitchen\" by Dave Jordan, became its only UK hit single, reaching #44 on 14 April. A disappointing result after a marketing campaign that included a new look for Scallon, a music video, life-size posters in major cities, and retailers receiving bonus [[flexi disc]]s. In Ireland it made #22. The album's title track was also released, followed by \"I Can't Get Over Getting Over You\", which she sang live on ''Top of the Pops'' in October, her final appearance on the show. The sad and reflective track \"Thieves of Paris\", written by Barry Blue and [[Lynsey de Paul]], has been rated one of the stand out tracks on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://macaenese5354.blogspot.com/2011_01_01_archive.html |title=\u9676\u9189\u7684\u516d\u4e03\u5341\u5e74\u4ee3\u60c5\u61f7: January 2011 |website=Macaenese5354.blogspot.com |date= |accessdate=2017-02-22}}</ref> They also wrote her 1972 single, \"Crossword Puzzle\", a #2 hit in Thailand.\n\nA new phase in her career began after [[Pope John Paul II]] came to Ireland in September 1979, inspiring her to write with her husband the Irish chart-topper, \"Totus Tuus\".\n\nOutside her chart career, Scallon had remained a popular personality since her 1970 Eurovision win. She had played the part of a [[Irish traveller|tinker]] girl in ''[[Flight of the Doves]]'' (1971), a children's adventure film starring [[Ron Moody]] and [[Jack Wild]] and directed by [[Ralph Nelson]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0067104/ imdb.com \u2013 ''Flight of the Doves'']</ref> She also performed in summer seasons at resorts and seasonal pantomimes as well as performing at venues such as the [[Royal Albert Hall]], the [[Royal Festival Hall]] and a week of sell-out shows at the [[London Palladium]]. Scallon also performed extensively in cabaret venues and was voted Top Female Vocalist at the National Club Acts Awards in 1979. [[BBC Television]] gave her two shows of her own: a series of ''[[A Day with Dana]]'' in 1974 and four series of ''Wake Up Sunday'' in 1979. For [[BBC Radio]] she presented a series of ''I Believe in Music'' in 1977.\n\n==1980s \u2013 Catholic music==\nHaving scored an Irish number one in January 1980 with the song that was based on the Pope's motto: [[Totus Tuus]], Latin for Totally Yours, the much larger American Christian market became a possible outlet for her music. Not long after returning home from a promotional visit to the [[National Religious Broadcasters]] conference in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], opened by [[Jimmy Carter|US President Jimmy Carter]], she was contacted by award-winning songwriter [[Kurt Kaiser]], vice president of [[Word Records]]. He invited her back to the USA where she was offered a recording contract. Meanwhile, [[Warwick Records (United Kingdom)|Warwick Records]] issued ''Everything is Beautiful'' in late 1980. Recorded in September at Pye Studios in London, the LP subtitled ''20 Inspirational Songs'' was advertised on TV and became her biggest-selling album in the UK, reaching #43 in the chart on 10 January 1981. It was followed later that year by ''Totally Yours'', her first Christian album for Word Records; the songs \"Praise the Lord\", \"The Soft Rain\" and \"Totus Tuus\" were credited to \"Dana and Damien Scallon\". As was \"Little Baby (Grace's Song)\", written while she was pregnant with their first child.\n\nShe was soon back in the studios again to make ''Magic'' in 1982, a pop album for Lite Records made at [[Morgan Studios]] and Maison Rouge Studios in London. It included four songs by her younger brothers John and Gerald Brown, as well as the single \"I Feel Love Comin' On\", written by [[Barry White]], which peaked at #66 in the UK on 22 May. Collaborating with her younger brothers they wrote the official Northern Ireland [[1982 FIFA World Cup]] song \"Yer Man\", and she recorded it with the full [[1982 FIFA World Cup squads|squad]] before they headed to Spain for the finals. Following this, her second album for Word was completed; ''Let There Be Love'' contained up-tempo Christian pop, jazz, ballads, and an old Irish hymn sung in Gaelic called [[Ag Criost an Siol]].\n\nScallon starred in a [[London's West End|West End]] production of ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'', staged at the [[Phoenix Theatre (London)|Phoenix Theatre]] during the 1983 Christmas and New Year pantomime season. The venues first panto broke box-office records and was extended into February. She played ''Snow White'' for over fourteen years, each time in a different city, beginning the run at the [[Hull New Theatre|New Theatre]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] in 1982.\n\nA tour of America took place in 1984 to promote her two Word albums. Appearances were made in concert halls, churches, colleges and also on TV and radio.\n\nAfter fifteen years in show business [[Hodder and Stoughton]] published ''Dana \u2013 An Autobiography'' in 1985. It told the story of her childhood, married life and music career, as well as her growing devotion to God. At the same time as her book launch came the release of her fifties tribute album ''If I Give My Heart to You'', featuring her last UK chart entry \"Little Things Mean a Lot\", #92 on 13 July 1985. In Ireland in made #27, as did the album's title track.\n\nDue to work commitments in 1979, she wasn't in the country when Pope John Paul II became [[Pope John Paul II's visit to Ireland|the first pope ever to visit Ireland]]. But she eventually saw him in 1987 at the Superdome in [[New Orleans]], having been invited there to perform \"Totus Tuus\" before a gathering of 80,000 or more. After her performance the [[pontiff]] made his way to the stage to personally thank her for writing the song.\n\n==1990s \u2013 Politics==\nSoon after completing a concert tour of England in early 1990, she took her family to [[Florida]] for an [[Easter]] holiday. Her break was interrupted by a request to fly to [[Irondale, Alabama]] and make a guest appearance at [[Eternal Word Television Network]]'s (EWTN) tenth anniversary show. Afterwards, the network's founder [[Mother Angelica]] enquired if her ex-hotelier husband would like to work there, setting up a retreat centre to look after the hundreds of visitors the network attracted each day. Then mid holiday she sang at a Rosary Rally in [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]], and was asked to write a theme song for the [[Rosary]]. The result was ''The Rosary'', an album released with [[Heart Beat Records]] in 1991 that has amassed over a million sales around the world.\n\nBy August 1991 the Scallons were living in [[Mountain Brook, Alabama|Mountain Brook]], close to EWTN's headquarters where Damien now worked. Thoughts of winding down her career were dashed when her husband was asked if his wife would like to work there, presenting a music programme. ''Say Yes'' became the first TV series she made for them. Three more followed: ''We Are One Body'', ''Backstage'' and ''Dana and friends''. With this exposure she became a popular Catholic music singer, appearing at conferences and public gatherings across America. [[Heart Beat Records]], the US Catholic music label, issued a number of her music and prayer albums.\n\nTo help celebrate the sixth [[World Youth Day]] event held in [[Cherry Creek State Park]], Denver in 1993, she was invited to sing in the presence of Pope John Paul II the theme song for the occasion, \"We Are One Body\", a song she composed herself. She also sang at the World Youth Day celebrations held in [[Paris]] in 1997, Toronto in 2002 and Sydney in 2008.\n\nIn June 1997, she received a letter from the Christian Community Centre in Ireland suggesting she run for the [[President of Ireland|Irish presidency]]. Having no interest in politics at the time, and never having heard of that organisation, she threw the \"incredible\" proposal in the bin. But they persisted and similar mail arrived from other people. Then the media got involved. She eventually agreed to seek nomination as a candidate in the [[1997 Irish presidential election]], standing as an [[Independent (politician)|independent]] under the name Dana Rosemary Scallon. Her campaign was based on the [[Constitution of Ireland|Irish Constitution]] and her belief that it could only be amended with the agreement of the Irish people by public ballot. She later became the first-ever presidential candidate to secure a nomination solely from County and City Councils, rather than from members of the [[Oireachtas]]. Polling day was 31 October, and Scallon received 175,458 of the first-preference votes (13.8%), coming third to [[Fianna F\u00e1il]]'s candidate and eventual winner [[Mary McAleese]]. Before returning to America she told reporters: \"I may not be a president, but I ''am'' a [[precedent]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.herald.ie/opinion/terry-prone-with-mary-on-for-the-aras-the-contest-really-hots-up-2658423.html |title=With Mary on for the Aras the contest really hots up |work=[[Evening Herald]] |author=Terry Prone |date=26 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe was granted US citizenship in 1999, requiring her to swear an [[Oath of Allegiance (United States)|oath]] renouncing allegiance to any other state.<ref name=\"Dana denies US passport deception\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1007/president.html |title=Dana denies US passport deception |publisher=RT\u00c9 |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheehan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/this-is-a-bid-to-discredit-me-i-wont-be-broken-2907429.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130218015034/http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/this-is-a-bid-to-discredit-me-i-wont-be-broken-2907429.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 February 2013 |title=This is a bid to discredit me -- I won't be broken |work=[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)]] |author=Maeve Sheehan |date=16 October 2011 }}</ref> That same year she again stood as an independent, this time winning a seat in the [[European Parliament]], representing Connacht\u2013Ulster. She campaigned on [[family values]] and her strong pro-life beliefs. Scallon is opposed to abortion in all cases, In 2013 she said \"there is no legal or constitutional obligation for politicians to legislate for the deliberate killing of an unborn child and there is no medical evidence to support this radical change to how we treat our mothers and their children and the taking of an innocent and defenceless human life can never be justified\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/dana-calls-for-referendum-on-abortion-law-1.1456045|title=Dana calls for referendum on abortion law|website=irishtimes.com|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> She was also vocal for her opposition to [[divorce]] and same sex marriage, along with a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]] line on the [[European Union|EU]]. Scallon refused to associate with any political party despite Fianna F\u00e1il making several approaches for her to join them.<ref name=\"rte.ie\">As revealed in an interview, Conversations with Eamon Dunphy, 3 November 2007, RT\u00c9 Radio 1 {{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/eamondunphy/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420233110/http://www.rte.ie/radio1/eamondunphy/ |archivedate=20 April 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> On becoming an [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] her eight-year stay in the US came to an end.\n\n==2000s to present==\nIn 2001 she opposed a proposed amendment to the Irish constitution that would have legalised the \"[[Emergency contraception|morning after pill]]\" and [[Intrauterine device|IUD]]. The amendment was defeated in a referendum in 2002, although it was supported by the mainstream political parties. Scallon also had public disagreements at the time with the Catholic hierarchy (notably with Cardinal [[Desmond Connell]]), the latter wishing instead to negotiate a consensus solution.<ref name=\"rte.ie\"/>\n\nAs an independent she unsuccessfully contested a seat in [[Galway West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Galway West]] in the 2002 Irish general election, scoring just 3.5% of the first preference vote. In June 2004, Scallon lost her European Parliament seat, taking 13.5% of the vote. Later that year she failed to secure a nomination to the office of President of Ireland against the uncontested incumbent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=4459 |title=Dana election results at Elections Ireland |website=Electionsireland.org |date= |accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nReturning to the world of entertainment in 2005, she spent seven weeks on the RT\u00c9 television series ''The Afternoon Show'', where she did a fitness routine with a trainer and lost fifteen pounds in weight in time for her eldest daughter's wedding. In 2006, she and dancer Ronan McCormack were paired together in the RT\u00c9 dance series ''[[Celebrity Jigs 'n' Reels]]''. They made it to the final show and came second. That same year, Scallon and her husband launched their own music label, DS Music Productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dana-music.com |title=DS Music Productions |website=Dana-music.com |accessdate=28 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926204058/http://www.dana-music.com/ |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> One of the first albums released was ''Totus Tuus'', a compilation of songs dedicated to the memory of Pope John Paul II and issued on the anniversary of his death. A children's album was released in 2007, along with a DVD in 2008, entitled ''Good Morning Jesus: Prayers & Songs for Children of All Ages'', which featured in a special series on EWTN. The Scallons and their new label were sued in 2007 by Heart Beat Records for copyright violations on several of the albums they'd recently released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dockets.justia.com/docket/court-iasdce/case_no-3:2007cv00066/case_id-34121/ |title=Heartbeat Records Inc v DS Music Production |website=Dockets.justia.com |date=20 July 2007 |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Gill & Macmillan]] published her second autobiography in 2007. Her political career took centre stage in ''All Kinds of Everything''. To coincide with the book launch, her first secular album since ''Forever Christmas'' a decade earlier, was released. ''A Thing Called Love'' was produced by her and her youngest brother Gerry, who also played guitar and keyboards, while her youngest son Robert played drums.\n\nIn 2009, Scallon became a judge on ''[[The All Ireland Talent Show]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waterford-news.ie/news/story.asp?j=27044&cat=entertainment |title=Waterford News & Star: |website=Waterford-news.ie |date= |accessdate=7 March 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in the summer of 2010 she participated in the Best of British Variety tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehaven-news.co.uk/home/dana-set-to-star-in-town-1.747397?referrerPath=features/the-arts |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505145337/http://www.whitehaven-news.co.uk/home/dana-set-to-star-in-town-1.747397?referrerPath=features/the-arts |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |title=Home &#124; Dana set to star in town |publisher=Whitehaven News |date=18 August 2010 |accessdate=7 March 2011 }}</ref> She was a contestant in the fourth series of the reality television programme, ''[[Celebrity Bainisteoir]]'', in 2011, but was forced to withdraw by RT\u00c9 when she announced she would run for the Irish presidency again.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/0715/celebritybainisteoir.html \"RT\u00c9's Celebrity Bainisteoirs announced\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817232359/http://www.rte.ie/ten/2011/0715/celebritybainisteoir.html |date=17 August 2011 }}. ''RT\u00c9 Ten''. 15 July 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.midulstermail.co.uk/sport/lissan_gac_1_3071674 \"Lissan GAC\"]. ''Mid Ulster Mail''. 27 September 2011.</ref>\n\n===2011 presidential campaign===\n{{Main|2011 Irish presidential election}}\nOn 19 September 2011, at the Fitzwilliam Hotel on [[St Stephen's Green]], Scallon announced she would be seeking a nomination to enter the following month's Irish presidential election.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/dana-seeks-help-from-all-sides-in-bid-to-nail-down-her-nomination-2881200.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120909020517/http://www.independent.ie/national-news/dana-seeks-help-from-all-sides-in-bid-to-nail-down-her-nomination-2881200.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 September 2012 |title=Dana seeks help from all sides in bid to nail down her nomination |publisher=Irish Independent |date=20 September 2011 |accessdate=20 September 2011 }}</ref> Carlow County Council was the first to nominate her.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newstalk.ie/2011/news/dana-get-first-aras-nomination-as-meetings-continue/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908102140/http://www.newstalk.ie/2011/news/dana-get-first-aras-nomination-as-meetings-continue/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=8 September 2012 |title=Dana get first Aras nomination, as meetings continue |publisher=Newstalk |date= |accessdate=26 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/carlow-votes-for-dana-522073.html |title=Carlow votes for Dana |publisher=Irish Examiner |date= |accessdate=26 September 2011}}</ref> She was then nominated by other county councils thus becoming a candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/dana-is-officially-a-presidential-candidate-following-offaly-nomination-238169-Sep2011/ |title=Dana is officially a presidential candidate following Offaly nomination |website=TheJournal.ie |date= |accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-15078509 |title=Dana in Irish presidential election after fourth council nomination |website=Bbc.co.uk |date= 27 September 2011|accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref> There were seven candidates in total, five men and two women.\n\nIn the first debate, held on [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]]'s ''[[RT\u00c9 News at One|News at One]]'', independent candidate Scallon explained she had delayed her entry into the race due to numerous family bereavements.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/0928/breaking4.html |title=\u00c1ras candidates set out positions in first debate |publisher=The Irish Times |date= |accessdate=28 September 2011 |first=Charlie |last=Taylor}}</ref> Appearing on ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]'' alongside the other candidates, Scallon displayed a copy of the EU Constitution, telling her audience: \"This is what this election is about. I have the knowledge and experience to be able to protect our sovereignty and that's the only question I think that's really urgent at this time.\" When asked by [[Ryan Tubridy]] if she would refuse to sign any bill threatening {{lang|ga|[[Constitution of Ireland|Bunreacht na h\u00c9ireann]]}}, she responded by saying, \"You bet your boots I would\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2011/1001/1224305088913.html |title=Campaigns to cost up to \u20ac350,000, say candidates |work=The Irish Times |date= 1 October 2011|accessdate=1 October 2011 |first1=Marie |last1=O'Halloran |first2=Paul |last2=Cullen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/1001/breaking3.html?via=mr |title=\u00c1ras candidates dodge bullets |work=The Irish Times |date= |accessdate=1 October 2011 |first=Paul |last=Cullen}}</ref> In fact, the President does not have such a veto power, being able only to refer a Bill to the Council of State for its consideration.<ref>[http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/upload/static/256.htm Article 26, Constitution of Ireland] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516102833/http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/upload/static/256.htm |date=16 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSpeaking on [[Newstalk]]'s ''[[The Right Hook]]'' programme on 5 October 2011, Scallon said: \"I am not anti Europe. I have always said that Europe, the concept of Europe is good. We want to be in Europe.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/dana-insists-i-am-not-anti-europe-246353-Oct2011/ |title=Dana insists: \u2018I am not anti-Europe\u2019 |publisher=The Journal |date= |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed on 7 October 2011 that Scallon had dual US and Irish citizenship, but she denied hiding this from the public, saying that her US citizenship, which involved her taking an [[oath of Allegiance (United States)|oath]] renouncing allegiance to Ireland, was not an issue then or now and she had no reason to hide it.<ref name=\"Dana denies US passport deception\"/>\n\nDuring a debate on ''[[Prime Time (Irish TV programme)|Prime Time]]'' ([[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]) on 12 October, Scallon read out a prepared statement towards the end of the debate, announcing that a \"malicious\" and \"false\" accusation had been made against her and her family in the United States and, while refusing to divulge any details, she said she would leave \"no stone unturned\" in her mission to track down the person or organisation responsible.<ref name=RTE_Debate_Live_12_Oct>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/1012/president_tracker.html|title=Live - Prime Time Debate: 2247|work=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=12 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/ojcweykfcwql/|title=Dana criticises \"vile and false\" accusation against member of her family|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=12 October 2011}}</ref> The incident was described as \"bizarre\" by some media.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://breakingnews.ie/ireland/dana-future-in-presidential-campaign-in-doubt-524131.html|title=Dana future in presidential campaign in doubt|work=Breakingnews.ie|date=12 October 2011}}</ref> It later transpired that the statement referred to her brother, John Brown, who had been accused in 2008, in the course of litigation in the US among family members, of having sexually abused his niece. He denied the allegation.<ref name=\"Sheehan\"/> Brown was arrested by London police in June 2012, following a complaint against him made in October 2011. In May 2013, he was charged with three counts of indecent assault on two girls aged under 16.<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/danas-brother-charged-with-child-molestation-in-uk-29289710.html \"Dana's brother charged with child molestation in UK\"], Independent.ie, 23 May 2013</ref> John Brown was found not guilty and unanimously cleared on all charges on 25 July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-28482986 |title=John Brown, brother of Dana, cleared of 1970s sex abuse charges |website=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> Marian Finnucan of RT\u00c9 said he was falsely accused<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rte.ie/radio1/marian-finucane/programmes/2014/0726/633234-marian-finucane-saturday-26-july-2014/?clipid=1638042 |title=Marian Finucane Saturday 26 July 2014 - Marian Finucane - RT\u00c9 Radio 1 |website=Rte.ie |date= |accessdate=2016-12-30}}</ref> John Brown has since taken legal action against his accusers and a journalist and newspaper.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nVoting took place on 27 October and the fourth and final count was completed two days later. Scallon received 51,220 votes (2.9%) and came sixth to [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour's]] [[Michael D. Higgins]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15488067 |title=Irish presidential election: Michael D Higgins elected |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date= 29 October 2011 |accessdate=29 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===2019 new album===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=January 2020}}\nIn 2019, Dana announced she was back in the studio and was recording a brand new album, her first in many years. Scallon appeared on [[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]], [[RTE Today]] and various radio stations to promote new single 'Falling'. The album 'My Time' was released on 1 November 2019.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 5 October 1978 she married hotelier Damien Scallon at [[St Eugene's Cathedral]] in Derry, where her parents were married. The couple first met in 1970 at his Ardmore Hotel in Newry, where a reception took place following a \"Dana Place\" street-naming ceremony in nearby Hilltown, to honour her recent Eurovision success. After a three-week honeymoon in [[Grenada]] {{citation needed|date=September 2018}} the newlyweds set up home in [[Rostrevor]], County Down.{{cn|date=January 2020}} They have four children: Grace (born 1981), Ruth (born 1983), John James (born 1984), and Robert (born 1989).{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe Scallons currently live in [[Claregalway]], [[County Galway]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.galwaynews.ie/21624-claregalway-resident-dana-intends-run-president |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120801131111/http://www.galwaynews.ie/21624-claregalway-resident-dana-intends-run-president |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 August 2012 |title=Claregalway Resident Dana Intends To Run For President |website=Galwaynews.ie |date=22 September 2011 |accessdate=28 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!'''Singles'''!!'''Albums'''<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 139}}</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"width:50%;\"|\n\n*1967 \"Sixteen\"\n*1968 \"Come Along Murphy\"\n*1968 \"Heidschi Bumbeidschi\"\n*1969 \"Look Around\"\n*1970 \"[[All Kinds of Everything]]\" (Ireland #1, UK #1, Austria #7, Germany #4, Netherlands #2, New Zealand #19, South Africa #7, Switzerland #7)\n*1970 \"I Will Follow You\"\n*1971 \"Who Put the Lights Out\" (Ireland #5, UK #14)\n*1971 \"Today\"\n*1971 \"[[Isn't It a Pity]]\"\n*1972 \"New Days...New Ways\"\n*1972 \"Crossword Puzzle\" (Thailand #2)\n*1973 \"Do I Still Figure in Your Life\"\n*1973 \"Sunday Monday Tuesday\" (Ireland #4)\n*1974 \"Please Tell Him That I Said Hello\" (Germany #27<sup>1</sup>, Ireland #7, UK #8<br/><sup>1</sup>as \"Spiel nicht mit mir und meinem Gl\u00fcck\")\n*1975 \"Are You Still Mad at Me\"\n*1975 \"It's Gonna Be a Cold Cold Christmas\" (Ireland #3 [1976 reissue #12], UK #4)\n*1976 \"[[Never Gonna Fall in Love Again]]\" (UK #31)\n*1976 \"Rivers Are for Boats\"\n*1976 \"Fairytale\" (Mexico #1, Germany #21, Austria #19, Belgium/Flemish Region #4, Netherlands #3, UK #13)\n*1976 \"[[I Love How You Love Me]]\" (Netherlands #27)\n*1977 \"Put Some Words Together\"\n*1979 \"Something's Cookin' in the Kitchen\" (UK #44, Ireland #22)\n*1979  \"The Girl is Back\"\n*1979 \"I Can't Get Over Getting Over You\"\n*1979 \"Totus Tuus\" (Ireland #1)\n*1980 \"[[When a Child is Born]]\"\n*1981 \"[[Lady of Knock]]\" (Ireland #23)\n*1981 \"[[Dream Lover]]\" (Ireland #26)\n*1982 \"[[Felice Taylor|I Feel Love Comin' On]]\" (UK #66)\n*1982 \"Yer Man\"\n*1982 \"You Never Gave Me Your Love\" / \"Marathon\"\n*1982 \"If You Really Love Me\"\n*1985 \"[[Little Things Mean a Lot]]\" (UK #92, Ireland #27)\n*1985 \"[[If I Give My Heart